Please merge patches into one.'}, {'account_id': 9382, 'date': '2015-04-28 18:26:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thai,

This is a new contributor and trying to understand the workflow to use the OpenStack gerrit review system. It was my understanding that if the change is small enough and the build works, 2 core members can +2 and approve a change. It seems to me that small changes like these are easy enough to review online, especially if the outcome of the patch is better documentation and adhering to a standard that is already defined. The end result of the patch is a better doc, why continue to -1 it and send the wrong message. Maybe you can suggest for the contributor to combine the patches into 1 in the future, or supply training documentation on how to do so. Different projects have different requirements, some groups prefer small patches, how would a new contributor even know this? Itâ€™s better to encourage new contributors, to mentor them, teach them and lead instead of rejecting so quickly with very little to no explanation.'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-04-29 16:35:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

That is a fair statement. However, I still prefer to see them merge as one patch. It's really just a capitalization change. My -1 is not intended to discourage, I am merely expressing my opinion. If another core strongly disagrees, they can still +2 and +A the patch through.

Besides, wouldn't this be a good exercise for a beginner? I'm not asking him to move mountains, just search and replace."}, {'account_id': 14920, 'date': '2015-04-29 16:58:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-04-30 09:27:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

This is a somewhat opinionated matter, and Thai's comment is totally valid. Generally speaking, it is useful to manage the size of the patches between 50 - 500 lines, IMO; too big and it becomes difficult to safely review the entire patch, but too small and it is just a little irritating having to review so many patches with the same topic.

That said, I don't think it is worth blocking on. In the future, please merge very small patches into one larger patch. We don't need 20 one-liners :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-30 09:27:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

commit_message:
Made changes per doc conventions to horizon.rst

changed file to comply with official doc conventions
horizon should be lowercase per the official name
and capitalization section in the wiki
documentation conventions for OpenStack
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions
Partial-bug: 1446253

Change-Id: Icdec9764535c509432b60ac2b3aee54da40d2085

commit_message:
Fix tempauth acl checks when simplejson has no speedups

As documented in linked bug report, tempauth unit tests
were seen to fail on a system where simplejson was
installed but without the speedups extension. This
is because the tempauth account acl validation checks
that values are type str, but without the speedups
extension the json parser is returning unicode objects.

Fix is to have the acl validator tolerate those objects
being unicode or str.

Also change common/bufferedhttp.py to coerce ring device
to type str when constructing a path, in order to avoid
a UnicodeDecodeError when httplib sends a message that
has non-ascii header values.

Change-Id: I01524282cbaa25dc4b6dfa09f3f4723516cdba99
Closes-Bug: 1425776

commit_message:
Use addCleanup in test_rebuild_server

Use addCleanup in test_rebuild_server to restore the test server
to its original image.

Change-Id: I69d3e20be7fb6ef38fd89f0132aff720ef87253e
Closes-bug: #1449563

[{'created': '2015-04-24 10:27:35.000000000', 'message': 'RN6.0-updates2 Messaging resolved issue

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: Icbd2ae016553b5e5c886205e87acf38f3ccec550

commit_message:
RN6.0-updates2 Ceilometer resolved issue

Resolved issues:

* PyMongo 2.6 causes memory leak;
* ceilometer-agent-notification can't connect
  after rabbitmq restart.

2nd bug is also described in the Known issues
section, so added info how to fix the bug.

Co-Authored-By: Maria Zlatkova <mzlatkova@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Olena Logvinova <ologvinova@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I1859874a3bfae5dff1e471e423d5f0f6a5f8691d

[{'created': '2015-04-22 08:43:33.000000000', 'message': 'Recover from POWERING-* state on compute manager start-up

If a compute manager is stopped / fails during POWERING-ON or
POWERING-OFF operations then the instance will be left stuck in
a transitional task_state.

This change handles both these states by simply either retriggering
the power on or power off request on start-up of the compute manager.
If the operation had previously completed then retrying will
essentially be a no-op so it is safe to handle instances in this
state in this way.

Closes bug: #1304333

(cherry picked from commit 8f7056f48c115ee0939c76ce08531dab0f14e354)
Change-Id: I262be6b13a764bc1355be34cdc0180e8e87f260b

commit_message:
Recover from POWERING-* state on compute manager start-up

If a compute manager is stopped / fails during POWERING-ON or
POWERING-OFF operations then the instance will be left stuck in
a transitional task_state.

This change handles both these states by simply either retriggering
the power on or power off request on start-up of the compute manager.
If the operation had previously completed then retrying will
essentially be a no-op so it is safe to handle instances in this
state in this way.

Closes bug: #1304333

(cherry picked from commit 8f7056f48c115ee0939c76ce08531dab0f14e354)
Change-Id: I262be6b13a764bc1355be34cdc0180e8e87f260b

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 105, 'name': 'Kyle Mestery', 'email': 'mestery@mestery.com', 'username': 'mestery'}, {'_account_id': 162, 'name': 'Bob Melander', 'email': 'bob.melander@gmail.com', 'username': 'bob-melander'}, {'_account_id': 261, 'name': 'Salvatore Orlando', 'email': 'salv.orlando@gmail.com', 'username': 'salvatore-orlando'}, {'_account_id': 2035, 'name': 'Maru Newby', 'email': 'marun@redhat.com', 'username': 'maru'}, {'_account_id': 2888, 'name': 'Mathieu Rohon', 'email': 'mathieu.rohon@gmail.com', 'username': 'mathieu-rohon'}, {'_account_id': 3217, 'name': 'Ian Wells', 'email': 'iawells@cisco.com', 'username': 'ijw-ubuntu'}, {'_account_id': 6820, 'name': 'Francois Eleouet', 'email': 'f.eleouet@gmail.com', 'username': 'fanchon'}, {'_account_id': 6854, 'name': 'YAMAMOTO Takashi', 'email': 'yamamoto@midokura.com', 'username': 'yamamoto'}, {'_account_id': 9594, 'name': 'David Welsch', 'email': 'dawelsch@cisco.com'}, {'_account_id': 11833, 'name': 'Mohammad Hanif', 'email': 'mhanif@brocade.com', 'username': 'mhanif'}, {'_account_id': 14605, 'name': 'vikram.choudhary', 'email': 'vikschw@gmail.com', 'username': 'vikram.choudhary'}]

[{'account_id': 3217, 'date': '2014-11-22 07:05:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3217, 'date': '2014-11-22 07:07:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-11-22 14:42:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-neutron-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/55/136555/2/check/gate-neutron-specs-docs/4ff6f6b/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 34s
- gate-neutron-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/55/136555/2/check/gate-neutron-specs-python27/85afdc4 : SUCCESS in 2m 08s'}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2014-11-25 15:53:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I have the same comment that during summit's session: it seems restritive to request the network to be created alongside with the edge ID, as it would prevent existing networks from being extended to the outside world. 

Appart from that, I definitevely agree with the rationale of having a simple API, and let the interconnection details outside of Neutron. Anyway, as a subsequent effort, wouldn't it make sense to have standard APIs describing these details? AWS & Azure already provide these kind of APIs, why wouldn't OpenStack have its own one?"}, {'account_id': 3217, 'date': '2014-11-30 06:33:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

My point is that a network controller may choose to deploy a network differently knowing that it's an edge network, and it can't do that if it can change status.

Also, you can make it an edge network but not connect anything to that edge until later.  The point of this, very explicitly, is that either side can use an edge ID first; so Neutron can use the edge ID and if nothing on the other side of the edge is using that same ID it's available for connection, but not actually connected to anything.  So I think your use case is covered, if not quite in the way you envisage."}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2014-12-02 09:12:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

For sure, some controller may need to deploy a specific technology for edge networks, and it would be easier to do that at network creation. But this limitation doesn't apply to every controller: some implementations enable to seamlessly plug existing neutron networks to the outside world.

IHMO, API design shouldn't encompass the limitation of specific implementations. If edge-ids were provided as independant ressources that tenants can attach to networks, a "limited" implementation could still raise error on net-update, and mandate to provide that ressource at net-create.'}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2014-12-03 04:46:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11833, 'date': '2014-12-03 23:59:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(7 comments)

There is a lot of detail missing from this spec.  It talks about interactions between OpenStack and an outside controller which are not explained.  Please see my comments inline.  Also, the purpose of introducing Neutron networks to the edge VPN can be achieved without extending the Neutron data model which is contrary to what this spec proposes.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-12-07 05:10:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(4 comments)

Are we able to make a call between this approach and "topological" approaches where all the details about the network extension are part of the API?

If the answer is not, we must find a way to allow both efforts to progress.
The best way for me is to neutron to not pick any winner, and let them envolve independently of neutron itself.'}, {'account_id': 9594, 'date': '2014-12-08 22:24:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-12-09 05:57:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

ECOSYSTEM PROJECT

This spec was given a -2 by the drivers team because the work proposed is of limited community appeal or lack of community consensus. The drivers team suggests that an extension project within the community ecosystem is a viable way forward.'}, {'account_id': 3217, 'date': '2014-12-10 04:18:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(10 comments)'}, {'account_id': 3217, 'date': '2014-12-10 04:26:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The specific issue with this being out-of-tree is that it changes an existing Neutron object in order to work to add an attribute, which implies a change to the data model and I worry that that would actually be problematic at upgrade/downgrade time.  It's specifically unlike, for instance, a network service, which generally attaches via the port interface as normal (versus this, which bridges onto a network).

Also, it's intended to enable out-of-tree development of edge networking APIs.

That said, I'll give it another revision and see if I can win people over.  If not, I guess we'll have to do without edge networking for yet another cycle."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-12-16 20:28:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I still do not understand why enabling out of tree development of edge networking APIs would need a core API change.

I think these APIs can come with their own extension which is loaded into the core providing the edge id functionality. however, since this is not clear to me, I'm temporarily removing the -2 to give more visibility to this spec.

In the meanwhile it would be good to have more details about the reference implementation which (if I'm not wrong) should be in the scope of this blueprint."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-12-17 22:28:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Without details on reference implementation we cannot approve the spec. Therefore without them this one is going to be delayed.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2014-12-18 22:42:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

DEFERRED UNTIL AFTER KILO

This spec was given a -2 by the drivers team because the work proposed does not fit within community priorities for Kilo. If there is additional capacity later in Kilo, the drivers may option to reactivate this spec.  Otherwise, the core team requests that you propose this in the 'L' cycle or later."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-01-26 15:08:30.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This review is > 4 weeks without comment and currently blocked by a core reviewer with a -2. We are abandoning this for now. Feel free to reactivate the review by pressing the restore button and contacting the reviewer with the -2 on this review to ensure you address their concerns.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-01-26 15:08:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This review is > 4 weeks without comment and currently blocked by a core reviewer with a -2. We are abandoning this for now. Feel free to reactivate the review by pressing the restore button and contacting the reviewer with the -2 on this review to ensure you address their concerns.'}, {'account_id': 2888, 'date': '2015-03-23 21:21:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(6 comments)'}]

commit_message:
Programmable cloud edge networks

Defines an API to allow external network controllers managing
networking beyond the cloud to pass traffic into specified Neutron
networks within the cloud.  Said networks may be as simple as
switch ports or as complex as encapsulations and overlays.

Change-Id: If3374f2b4da4a681fd49ac41f60fc25d4905d3c3

commit_message:
Log waiting time for node bootstrapping

We had a staging tests failure (see the bug referenced below) which was
caused by 3 of 5 nodes not comming up in time. Right now we don't know
how much time it takes 5 nodes to come up normally. Maybe 10 minutes is
barely enough and we just need to increase timeout? We will not know that
for sure until we log the time and see how much time it takes on average.
This change introduces such logging.

Change-Id: I342f6997f74d2d42dcf772fb5e2f597122d54a94
Related-Bug: #1435837

commit_message:
Fix TypeError exception during cancel stack update

TypeError: call() takes exactly 3 arguments(5 given) is raised
during cancel stack update, this patch will fix the problem.

Change-Id: If85389150a15575d9e01466d950f8c07b8fa2717
Closes-Bug: #1448384

commit_message:
Use openstack common util method to find name-or-id resource

Currently, the keystone commands support name-or-id, like this:
    keystone --debug user-role-list --tenant-id admin
But, if we specified tenant_id of "--tenant-id" parameter of above
command, keystoneclient will still try to get the tenant at first,
that is inefficient, it is better to directly use the tenant_id to
get user-role relationship firstly. This flaw can be find by
specifying "--debug" option with above command. The openstack common
util method "find_resource" has optimized that, this change switch
keystonclient to use it.

Change-Id: I0264567320ab8f77bb832c5f8613361069172c2d
Closes-Bug: #1450276

commit_message:
Allow deployer to choose Ceilometer backend

Ceilometer can use different backends. A recent change moved backend
support for Ceilometer from MySQL to MongoDB. This commit introduce a
greater flexibility, letting the deployer choose wheter MySQL or MongoDB
should be used as a backend for Ceilometer.

Change-Id: I0d5bfb0763cbcee234df7ab13574d866743d5ddf

commit_message:
Use snapshot's environment when stack restore

Using snapshot's enviroment instead of current stack's
enviroment when stack restore.

Change-Id: I7becfbe4b970820bd374560d00fa6f661a85bdab
Closes-Bug: #1430673

commit_message:
Fix BM nodes extension to deal with missing node properties

The os-baremetal-nodes extension currently relies on the presence
of specific properties on the Ironic nodes.  This can result in
KeyError exceptions if there are nodes in the Ironic inventory
without these (specifically: cpus, memory_mb, local_gb).  This
updates the extension to avoid the KeyError. This is consistent
with how the Ironic driver calculates resources from nodes.  That
is, nodes that are missing a specific property are simply considered
to provide 0 resources of that type.

This is a backport of commit 7b0721f5997c86e0ef3c51c4a60a8f667c93812a

Change-Id: I1c30d5100b01a3e8cbce5185b5adeb8b5ce48aa0
Closes-Bug: #1423427

'}, {'created': '2015-04-28 17:31:45.000000000', 'message': 'Add partial stateful-only backup of Fuel

Defaults now to stateful-only backup.
New option dockerctl backup [path] --full
will include the following:
 * /etc/puppet
 * /var/www/nailgun
 * docker container backups

dockerctl restore now defaults to stateful-only
restore. --full option is necessary to restore
Docker containers. All system directory backups,
however, will be restored regardless of --full
option.

System directory backup now pauses any running
containers before packing files to minimize
inconsistencies.

Added postgres DB dump to backup, but not restore
because in-place restore is adequte, but DB dumps
can be useful for serious troubleshooting if a
need arises.

blueprint master-stateful-only-backup

Change-Id: Ifc1d086a2eb15c0ea03d3ffdd2795a1f99d1c092

commit_message:
Add partial stateful-only backup of Fuel

Defaults now to stateful-only backup.
New option dockerctl backup [path] --full
will include the following:
 * /etc/puppet
 * /var/www/nailgun
 * docker container backups

dockerctl restore now defaults to stateful-only
restore. --full option is necessary to restore
Docker containers. All system directory backups,
however, will be restored regardless of --full
option.

System directory backup now pauses any running
containers before packing files to minimize
inconsistencies.

Added postgres DB dump to backup, but not restore
because in-place restore is adequte, but DB dumps
can be useful for serious troubleshooting if a
need arises.

blueprint master-stateful-only-backup

Change-Id: Ifc1d086a2eb15c0ea03d3ffdd2795a1f99d1c092
Doc-Impact: ops

commit_message:
Switch FQDN/hostname entries in Heat hosts

This is needed so that `facter fqdn` and `hostname -f` print the same
result which is needed for `puppet apply` to run.

Change-Id: I0fdc1fed5b749db5e99530ebe9a429012d7b31bb
Partial-Bug: #1447497

commit_message:
Adding script for retrieving OpenStack action list

 * It is simple CLI tool.
 * Script now works fine for: Nova, Keystone,
   Glance, Heat and Cinder.
 * in case of Keystone, user must provide full
   auth_info and use v3 auth_url.

TODO:
 * Think on optimal way to do it for neutron.

commit_message:
Forbid booting of QCOW2 images with virtual_size > root_gb

Currently, it's possible to boot an instance from a QCOW2 image,
which has virtual_size bigger than one allowed by the given flavor
(root_gb).

The issue is caused by two different problems in the code:

1) typo in get_disk_size() has made it always return None and
   effectively disabled verify_base_size() checks

2) Rbd image backend skips the verify_base_size() step for
   'cached' images (the one with base files), so it is possible to
   boot an instance using a larger flavor once and then use smaller
   flavors to boot the same image, even if allowed root_gb size is
   smaller than the image virtual size

Closes-Bug: #1429093

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py
	nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_imagebackend.py

Change-Id: I383130e5f8cc288f4b428ed43fe4d3aba7169473
(cherry picked from commit c1f9ed27af64e6893d9d0153a964df5aba99b8f0)

I'm fine with the idea of getting drivers on board with this. Ideally though, I don't want the matrix to exist. I don't want drivers choosing the timeline of when they want to implement certain features. This will result in some drivers doing some features. We spoke about this in the last midcycle meetup, but I would like to see features graduate into the BaseVD at some point. This will involve coordination with the drivers, but something I'm willing to do like CI's, but in order to achieve a consistent user experience regardless of driver and avoid NotImplementedErrors raised in the background from users."}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-04-27 02:44:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

A helpful recommendation to go with my comment, I think it would be good to establish in a spec the goal I mentioned in my previous comment. New features are introduced in a release. How long do we give drivers to implement that feature? What happens if they don't? This is excellent progress Marc. :)"}, {'account_id': 7872, 'date': '2015-04-27 08:33:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7872, 'date': '2015-04-27 08:34:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Unblock master gating

Most of master is transitioning to the liberty cycle, to allow us
to continue gating the service install versions is being set back
to the head of the stable/kilo branch. This should be updated once
all upstream OpenStack projects fully transition to Liberty.

This adds a wait condition when creating the containers to ensure
that the containers are created correctly and that ssh is available
within them before actually continuing with the installation process

This change forces the apt mirrors to use a set that is known good.
The previous changes to set the mirrors to the same as what was
already on the host has proven itself to be a greater issue by not
using a set that is known to be in good working order.

Change-Id: I1872a32b53b9caecb8ac0803db304fa0ee254475
Closes-Bug: 1441148

commit_message:
Use separate toctree directives for user vs admin

Including a document in a toctree and then excluding it with a meta
condition confuses the next/previous link generation. Use completely
separate toctrees instead.

Change-Id: I96c15ad37f0bd89e40d2351ffe85aa9d15ab1aff

commit_message:
Provide the RabbitMQ OCF backport guide

This update to the ops guide describes how
to backport the RabbitMQ OCF script from the
6.0.x / 5.1.x trunc branches to the existing
Fuel 6.0/5.1 installations

Add details about managing OpenStack services
in ops guide as it was missing.

Closes-bug: #1440018

Change-Id: Ia05b5d01fee4e933f64d6cd5ad0d4c28622cc54e
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix get_ml2_port_bond_data() return code

The method returned {None} which is a set containing None.
I assume the correct result was just returning None

Also the calling method didn't properly handle the case where None (or
the original set) were returned.

Change-Id: I109e4f9c45cba1884be8fd7fca0c3a38d4802f16
Signed-off-by: Saggi Mizrahi <saggi.mizrahi@huawei.com>

commit_message:
Move incorrect error printing

The error message is printed for every none router port
but VM ports are also synced.
move the printing to the correct place and change severity
to info

Change-Id: I9c79758d31dc7450af36405029565802e149f93f
Closes-Bug: #1432303

commit_message:
remove qos tests from volume smoke tag

These go well beyond the scope of basic resource testing for the smoke
tag, we should delete these to trim down the smoke tag to a more
minimal set.

Change-Id: I57e49dcb247cad2da2c06296196dc22d6257e353

commit_message:
trim network smoke tests

This massively trims down the network api smoke tests to remove all
tests which require an optional extension from the tag, and pair down
what's left to a set of CRUD type tests for most of the major
resources. Additional tests for those resources which tested either
edge conditions, extra attributions, or field filtering are dropped
from the smoke tag as well.

Change-Id: Ia3472da9b0ef3103560ca23b5736dc6b492b1860

remove smoke tag from admin tests

remove the smoke test from the admin tests. The smoke tag should
really be a small set of positive user level tests of function, admin
only tests really don't fit in this category.

commit_message:
Changing "Data Processing" to "Data processing"

According to our conventions "Data processing" is the correct
capitalization.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions

commit_message:
remove smoke tag from negative tests

the smoke tag should be a small set of representative tests to ensure
something is working, negative tests are beyond scope of what should
be in this tag.

Change-Id: Icf41b8d38ea71d887d91f7797d8fa061bb6209fb

subject: not all scenario tests should be in smoke

commit_message:
not all scenario tests should be in smoke

The decision to include all of scenario by default makes for an
extremely heavy test of tests in smoke, we should instead only include
specific scenario tests that expose some basic sanity
checking. Advanced scenario tests should be dropped from this list.

This change means we no longer have to exclude 'slow' tests, as we'll
just tag the right tests with smoke.

Change-Id: I34aa8aa9274e02bb68f62863d64c47ba9916f2e4

commit_message:
Issue #1450210: Preversioning rc tag handling

We were generating versions lower than the last tag when preversioning
was in use and pre-release versions had been tagged.

Also attempt to run the script without devstack.

commit_message:
Allow plugin to specify router_id

It is useful to allow the backend to specify the uuid that we want neutron to
use. We currently do this same thing for networks. This patch enables the same
behavior for routers as well.

Change-Id: If675dfd2997217886976301270ef5f773ffa7a13

commit_message:
Add ability to configure cinder backups

This commit adds the configuration for the cinder-backup service to the
cinder.conf template (specifically at this time only support for the
swift driver is included)

Additionally, plays are added to start the cinder-backup service on the
cinder-volumes containers (this behaviour mirrors what is currently in
master).

Whilst not a cherry-pick, this work is modelled on similar work in
master

Partial-bug: #1399386
Change-Id: I6f3353210277c344c191f226c2e8d11bf5822419

commit_message:
Add n-cauth into defalut services

n-cauth work with n-novnc to provide the vnc service for VMs.

Change-Id: Ia5c53aaaf7fe4f881d525a31b097b167fdb8e5c8
Closes-Bug: #1447774

commit_message:
Add parent field to project creation

Adding the possibility to create projects hierarchies by adding
the parent field in the create project call.

Co-Authored-By: Victor Silva <victor@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Implements: bp hierarchical-multitenancy

commit_message:
Add NoDiskSpaceException

vSphere APIs such as ExtendVirtualDisk_Task, CopyVirtualDisk_Task
throw NoDiskSpace fault when there is insufficient datastore
space. Currently, VMwareDriverException is thrown by oslo.vmware in
response to NoDiskSpace VIM fault. This patch adds a new exception
class corresponding to NoDiskSpace fault.

Change-Id: I50c5a93aae7fa2b5ad29951eec4d5a07e4f02045

[{'created': '2015-04-27 13:00:16.000000000', 'message': "Fixes wrong folder for listing tests

oslo.serialization had ./tests in its .testr.conf instead of just .,
which as a result didn't run the tests inside ./oslo_serialization.
This is quite bad, because what's important right now is the new
tests in the non-namespace folder. This patch fixes this, and allow
to run all tests.

Change-Id: Ic8d7409b214864d6350c76fd6d86c430a7380e8c
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes wrong folder for listing tests

oslo.serialization had ./tests in its .testr.conf instead of just .,
which as a result didn't run the tests inside ./oslo_serialization.
This is quite bad, because what's important right now is the new
tests in the non-namespace folder. This patch fixes this, and allow
to run all tests.

Change-Id: Ic8d7409b214864d6350c76fd6d86c430a7380e8c

commit_message:
Fix snapshot image/backup residue in backend

Set resource data 'snapshot_image_id' of server and
'backup_id' of volume immediately after creating the
image and backup while snapshoting. Otherwise there
will image/backup residue in backend.

Change-Id: Id7441f0c9d537b417488c2857019802872239b2e
Closes-Bug: #1448842

commit_message:
Update secgroup API for new get/list/search API

Security group API now conforms to the new get/list/search
interface. Instead of a Nova object being returned, we now return
a dict (or list of dicts).

commit_message:
Update flavor API for new get/list/search API

The flavor API methods now support the get/list/search style interface.
This required changing the format of the flavor list from a list of
{flavor_id: flavor_obj} dicts to a list of converted flavor dicts.

Change-Id: I593493c16f441470e9f210592c4baf2fa81664b5

commit_message:
Support to generate hot template based on resource type

Currently heat supports to create CFN template based on
the given resource type. And this patch adds an option
to allow user to specify template type to generate(support
HOT template at the same time).

blueprint support-to-generate-hot-templates

Change-Id: I55cfb9b0f87e638350f2f6367fb399d772fff7e1

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I5da7ca7a8a909eb12a4417e7d5f5b6bd33da4de8

commit_message:
Fix scheduling notifications handler: InstanceScheduled

Currently, the InstanceScheduled class cannot handle the instance
scheduling notifications from nova with the current format. This
change fix the issue.

Change-Id: I0e3df13ba6ac5ddb779dd6e683bbf9160d123481
Closes-Bug: #1386178

commit_message:
Signaling SoftwareDeployment resources via Swift

Currently the only option for signaling a deployment resource requires making
an authenticated API request to heat. A SoftwareDeployment resource
signal_transport: TEMP_URL_POLL will allow unauthenticated signaling using a
similar approach to OS::Heat::SwiftSignal.

Change-Id: I0847474a28656834685975a1fbb31f455a54ae25

commit_message:
Add flag to trigger task interface for rackspace

It turns out that the task interface for upload is not implied by v2
glance api. Add a boolean flag that can be consumed elsewhere.

Change-Id: I2cdcfe302a73ebfa7f739399c1eeb3bc9f96ab3c

Honestly patch3 would have been the one I expect to be correct. ODL isn't going to grant elevated access rights to non-ODL bots on one of our channels.

Is there a way to not have accessbot also have to be in the channel that the gerritbot is in?"}, {'account_id': 6609, 'date': '2015-04-27 18:11:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

No, it's a hard requirement, we won't put bots in channels the openstackinfra account doesn't have the specified access to."}, {'account_id': 10354, 'date': '2015-04-27 18:27:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Even though the gerritbot is literally only a participant entity? That's actually rather silly. There are no controls in gerritbot that would be needed for elevated rights as it needs at most +V if the channel requires that to be set (ours don't). Requiring that another bot (that has elevated rights) be in the same channel just for a speaker bot to live in a channel is rather poor form."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2015-04-27 18:59:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The OpenStack Project Infrastructure Team does not, as a policy, operate IRC bots in any over which channels its administrators lack control. Use of these bots is not mandatory, however, and we already have them emit information in plenty of other public channels you can join, for which you can configure them to also emit events for your projects.'}, {'account_id': 6609, 'date': '2015-04-27 19:00:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

The gerritbot code is open source, so you're welcome to run your own if you can't meet our requirements: https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/gerritbot"}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2015-04-27 19:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Sorry, fingers got ahead of brain. What I meant was that The the OpenStack Project Infrastructure Team does not, as a policy, operate IRC bots in any channels over which its administrators lack control.

This is primarily a means of ensuring we can properly diagnose issues with the bots and be able to adjust other permissions on those channels which may needed for them to operate properly.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-04-28 20:01:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Before I abandon this patch, I'd just like to reiterate what I'd really like and what the intention of this patch was:

An existing Freenode channel (#opendaylight-neutron) exists which is currently used by the OpenDaylight side of the ODL/Neutron integration team. It has a bot posting ODL gerrit comments. In trying to have a single place for ODL/Neutron developers, I wanted the OpenStack gerritbot to post in this channel.

Just posting the above to make sure folks are on the same page in case there is a way around the current roadblock. If not, I'll abandon this in 24 hours. Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-04-30 01:47:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

I tried, but I could not get the OpenDaylight and OpenStack to play nicely together. :('}]

http://goo.gl/mz8ocj

"}]
commit_message:
n-net: turn down log level when vif isn't found in deallocate_fixed_ip

Logstash shows that within 7 days this error shows up over 16,000 times
and 85% of those jobs are successful.

http://goo.gl/mz8ocj

Given bug 968457 was reported in 2012 and nothing has been adjusted
since to address this race, we can assume it's not an error condition
that justifies the ERROR log level, so let's tone it down to INFO.

Related-Bug: #968457

Change-Id: I050a8915349da39530433edaba49c1e781e6d692

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-22 12:12:20.000000000', 'message': 'Correct inconsistent enable_snat management

Neutron reset enable_snat attribute when external_gateway_info is
cleared but not when external_gateway_info is only updated which
implies the following sets of actions have different behaviors:

  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub1 --disable-snat
  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub2

enable_snat is False after the last command

  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub1 --disable-snat
  neutron router-gateway-clear router1
  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub2

enable_snat is True after the last command (router-gateway-clear reset
enable_snat).

This change proposes not to reset the attribute enable_snat when
external_gateway_info is cleared. Moreover this change optimizes
_update_router_gw_info by performing a db update onyl when enable_snat
is updated.

Change-Id: Ibab289936c55b1cf9614b44a4f18f54c959ee9e8
Closes-Bug: #1384146
'}, {'created': '2014-10-22 15:35:28.000000000', 'message': 'Correct inconsistent enable_snat management

enable_snat is False after the last command

  neutron router-gateway-clear router1
  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub2

enable_snat is True after the last command (router-gateway-clear reset

commit_message:
Correct inconsistent enable_snat management

Neutron resets enable_snat attribute when external_gateway_info is
cleared but not when external_gateway_info is only updated which
implies the following sets of actions have different behaviors:

  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub1 --disable-snat
  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub2

enable_snat is False after the last command

  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub1 --disable-snat
  neutron router-gateway-clear router1
  neutron router-gateway-set router1 pub2

enable_snat is True after the 2nd command resets the gateway AND
enable_snat.

This change proposes to always reset the attribute enable_snat when
enable_snat is not provided in external_gateway_info on POST/PUT for
consistency.

APIImpact
Change-Id: Ibab289936c55b1cf9614b44a4f18f54c959ee9e8
Closes-Bug: #1384146

commit_message:
Fix functional tests to run against live clouds

It's possible a developer may have a test account on a live cloud,
rather than a devstack. To support this, we should not make assumptions
about content put into a cloud by devstack, but should request things we
want - such as "the smallest flavor you have".

Keep the attempt to use the cirros image to continue to support
devstack, but fall back to the first ubuntu image found, since that's
the most likely to be cached on compute hosts on public clouds.

Change-Id: I6f0336d02cf924b3657fdc42bd151d11d5e3a6be

commit_message:
change floatingip_subnet to ListOpt

For deployment, MultiStrOpt is a bit more difficult to deal with than
ListOpt so let's switch floatingip_subnet over to ListOpt while we still
can.

Change-Id: Idc2dc582a80993b9de98785ded31cc90ee44f781
(cherry picked from commit 34c351a62e3e03016534c1707f95c826b390a3c5)

commit_message:
Trigger an action in a software-config component

OS::Heat::SoftwareComponent now allows non-lifecycle configs to be specified.
This feature will make it possible to trigger these configs and monitor their
progress and results.

Specifies: blueprint software-config-trigger
Change-Id: I56180f4a7aaaa5c47508f3133258110f34d129fd

commit_message:
Do not cache unsteady state images

States that are expected to change should not be cached, as this will
just prolong any polling loops to detect the changes. This also makes
for less invalidations as we can depend on the fact that the cache will
only ever contain steady states.

Change-Id: Ie241db6311540725d24dcc6328f6f965820baf1b

commit_message:
Preserve file attributes when copying image dirs for build

Add "-a" to preserve file attributes so that unnecessary Docker image
build can be avoided. Otherwise, build-all-docker-images will generate
additional image layer due to timestamp change.

Change-Id: I893fa0637937c521198f50b1bba203a27c9f00a3
Closes-Bug: 1449287

Add tests and invalidation for glance v2 upload

This coverage exposed python3 incompatibilities, and also revealed that
some more caches needed invalidating both before and after update.

commit_message:
Enfore key sorting for serializers

The sorting of keys is not enforced, which is causing some mismatches
for some strict testing. This patch enforce the sorting of keys when
doing JSON dumps.

Change-Id: I31ce5fa5e753cbf287429ad689752353530a4b4f

1) add a metadata entry for all servers created by Senlin, which can be
used later on for scaling filter's purpose, for example. 2) removed the

commit_message:
Revised metadata support

1) add a metadata entry for all servers created by Senlin, which can be
used later on for scaling filter's purpose, for example. 2) removed the
old 'meta' interface which is being substituted by 'metadata'. 3) Make
profile base capable of doing additional operations when node membership
change. 4) Enable nova server profile to handle the join/leave operation
where metadata is changed.

Change-Id: If8789c8a59c9a04e0342d08d5a79dc289704d735

Use /opt/git directly

This avoids a chunk of unneeded IO and allows us to stop depending on
devstack being run.

commit_message:
Apply topology_template to tosca_template

Using TopologyTemplate in tosca_template to replace Input, Output,
NodeTemplates and RelationshipTemplates.
But keeping the functions to allow users to get above resources from
ToscaTemplate.
Modified testing templates with 'topology_template' section.

partially implements: bp tosca-topology-template

Change-Id: If3007c81d51f271a53c9940924f46e79a7648021

commit_message:
Add endpoint and service ids to fixtures

The service catalog should contain an endpoint id and service id in the
v3 token and an endpoint id in the v2 token.

commit_message:
Exclude ruby from CentOS repo

Since there are 2 version in repo, ruby should be excluded. That allows
to run 'yum upgrade' or 'yum check-update'
https://review.openstack.org/177251 should be reverted once this patch
getis merged

Change-Id: I31dd269cd1a83ff08a28574cd6d084721e248125
Closes-Bug: 1448114

commit_message:
Tests assert 200 on POST operations instead of 201

The POST operations in test_content_types.py assert that the expected_status
is a 200, instead of 201. According to the v2.0 API documentation, POST
operations should result in 201 Created.

Related-Bug: #1403509

Change-Id: I8e5775ead1c910dac89622479c239cdd56b93ba0

pycadf now supports Python3

Adding pycadf back into the requirements file so that we can remove the
magic mocking.

bp python3

(3 comments)

Yes, I think we're missing a couple of backlevel version changes.

John, we historically haven't had a lot of testing of non-mainline rpc versions like this. What we do have is a little synthetic, as Hans points out. We do test this in the grenade tests, both with the old/mixed version and the new version. However, they're casts for those three calls, so we're probably not noticing that they're failing.

Aside from needing a couple more of those versions tested, I think this is good. Hans, are you able to jump right on those, or should I amend your patch?

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-04-27 14:02:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add security group calls missing from latest compute rpc api version bump

The recent compute rpc api version bump missed out on the security group
related calls that are part of the api.

One possible reason is that both compute and security group client side
rpc api:s share a single target, which is of little value and only cause
mistakes like this.

This change eliminates future problems like this by combining them into
one to get a 1:1 relationship between client and server api:s.

Change-Id: I9207592a87fab862c04d210450cbac47af6a3fd7
Closes-Bug: #1448075

commit_message:
debian-minimal: Remove -backport's restricted + universe

These are ubuntu-isms that do not exist on debian mirrors and cause
builds to break if they're based on a stable debian release.

Change-Id: I08c2826eba4aabd0be69955220624b2f179a15ee
Closes-bug: #1450198

commit_message:
Populating job type choices via api call

Rather than hard-code the choices for the job type
dropdown, they are now generated from an api call
that factors-in currently loaded plugins.  Also updated
the tests to utilize the new call.

Change-Id: I69f7100335bd35a891f23efd286da784c3d34e9f
Closes-Bug: #1371285

commit_message:
Make sure OVS restarts when Exception occurred

This fix let flows in br-tun automatically recover from an Exception,
which is an ideal situation.
Simplly improve a missed flag will make sure OVS restart properly
after we walked out of Exception loop.

Change-Id: Id0ac9399ec39fef19ce71566670ed245c681192e
Closes-Bug: #1439472

commit_message:
tests: confirm that _output_hosts_file does not log too often

I3ad7864eeb2f959549ed356a1e34fa18804395cc didn't include any regression unit
tests to validate that the method won't ever log too often again,
reintroducing performance drop in later patches. It didn't play well
with stable backports of the fix, where context was lost when doing the
backport, that left the bug unfixed in stable/juno even though the patch
was merged there [1].

The patch adds an explicit note in the code that suggests not to add new
log messages inside the loop to avoid regression, and a unit test was
added to capture it.

Once the test is merged in master, it will be proposed for stable/juno
inclusion, with additional changes that would fix the regression again.

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/linux/dhcp.py
	neutron/tests/unit/test_linux_dhcp.py

Local changes:
- remove LOG.debug messages that sneaked into the for loop with a
  backport.

Related-Bug: #1414218
Change-Id: I5d43021932d6a994638c348eda277dd8337cf041
(cherry picked from commit 3b74095a935f6d2027e6bf04cc4aa21f8a1b46f2)

commit_message:
Slave nodes are not booted

We restart all the NICs of master node after we ensure Cobbler is
ready. Restarting NIC breaks network connection between Cobbler
and outgoing physical network. Added another restart of the docker
container after network restart.

Change-Id: I0bbba2fbad801e109f52ee5fbcf203b8ba7d1dd8
Closes-Bug: #1427227
(cherry picked from commit 27634ecd26834d5242b7707b9e463ea90b9cf1bf)

commit_message:
Refactor assignment driver internal clean-up method names

As indicated by the TODO comment, two of the clean-up method
names in the assignment driver do not follow the logical pattern
of delete_<entity>_assignments(). This patch fixes this.

Change-Id: Iebc20b9bc7720fbfa0054888024f4aa12e83f42d
Closed-bug: 1438517

commit_message:
Merge create-backup functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges create-backup functional tests.

Change-Id: I3edd045fa61e4e6469fce6ccc9d49e4f400c089f

commit_message:
Share hide server add tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges hide server addresses functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: I8c467050ea3ed666c3837d9c2846ae5d9b245c69

commit_message:
Do not delete LP images

We are seeing random docker load failures in performance tests, and we
think it is due to a potential concurrency issue in docker load and rmi.
So this patch avoids the deletion of LP images.

Change-Id: Ia415c2a0d3e10bb3477399c2ca8464921646ab06

commit_message:
RequestSpec object split instance_properties

To prepare for later uses of the RequestSpec object, and so that it can
be more explicit about what is available for use during scheduling, the
instance that has been shoved into instance_properties has been split
into the component pieces that are used by current scheduler filters.

vm_state and task_state are used as well, but only for the host state
consume_from_instance method and they are never different between
requests so we can leave them out of there.

image_ref is used for one filter but should be available in
requestspec.image.

Change-Id: I5744367ce395dac1d300a740f67c0a17668dd952

commit_message:
Update README to work with release tools

The README file needs to have links to the project documentation and bug
tracker in a parsable format in order for some of the release tools
scripts to work (particularly the one that prints the release note
email).

Change-Id: I37e0acc5ed8e1af565359290fa622456901c735e

Why are we removing list, delete operations in schema validation. This is something we plan to support in Liberty. Till now, its new feature, only available at server side. There are client side changes which yet to happen so there should not be any version issue. Even if there, it can be clarified in API docs.

If this is removed, then supporting those operations on secret and container will require code change. If leave as-is, then the changes are only in policy definition which is relatively easier to change. Also we are losing number of tests related to those operation as part of this change.'}, {'account_id': 11561, 'date': '2015-04-27 20:39:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I suggest this patch only go in Kilo, and not to Liberty.
(Or if it goes into master, then it can be reverted when the time is right.

The problem with having unimplemented parameters available in the API of a shipping release is that there is no indication to the user that the requested action failed.

For example, a Liberty client might connect to a Kilo Server and mark a secret as write private, read the ACL data and see that a secret is marked as write private, but really the secret is not protected by that ACL.'}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2015-04-28 21:28:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

I agree with Dave.  Unimplemented features should return 400s.  To add support for additional roles in the ACL should start with a Liberty blueprint, and the implementation should change the Validation to accept only the new roles that are added.'}, {'account_id': 1091, 'date': '2015-04-28 23:44:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

For supporting other operations behavior, its more of policy modification and not changing code e.g. if I want to allow ACL users (e.g. cloud admin or high privileged user) to 'delete' a secret, it can be done by just modifying policy rules around https://github.com/openstack/barbican/blob/master/etc/barbican/policy.json#L28 . You don't need to have project specific role for that operation.

This is a new feature and there is no barbican client support. I will recommend not to remove this feature support from Liberty code base and if needed, just make change in kilo branch only."}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2015-04-29 03:26:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Arun, I'm not sure I understand your concern.  This CR adds validation such that only the values described in the API Impact section of the spec are accepted. [1]  This CR does not remove any functionality from the service.

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/barbican-specs/specs/kilo/add-creator-only-option.html#rest-api-impact"}, {'account_id': 11561, 'date': '2015-04-29 14:34:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm confused too.  Is the only thing missing to support ACLs for write, list, and delete a change to policy.json?  In that case, shouldn't we update the default policy.json to fully include this feature?"}, {'account_id': 1091, 'date': '2015-04-29 19:14:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Checked the code again around secrets delete, code change is needed and its just not policy change. commit_message:
Remove Future Parameters (write, list, delete) from ACL Validation Schema

Updated the validation schema for ACLs.
  - Removed write, list, and delete operations since they are not yet supported.
  - Added line for no additional properties other than "users" and "creator_only"
  - Added unit tests covering all of these and other conditions.
  - Updated unit tests to limit to "read" ACLs
  - Removed unit tests covering cases with more than one operation

Change-Id: Ie8a3abd22d02bb4a7bbedad373efa7435f3bdb3b
Closes-Bug: #1447872

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package.

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I4e1cb4f1caaee61683dc9fb0ffc67e8f9e06dc6d

commit_message:
Support add multiple images/tenants in members

The member-create and member-delete commands now allow multiple images
and tenants to be added with one command.

Before, we could only run:
    1) glance member-create <IMAGE> <TENANT_ID>
    2) glance member-delete <IMAGE> <TENANT_ID>

Now, we can create/delete multiple images and tenants:
    1) glance member-create --images <IMAGE> [<IMAGE> ...]
                            --tenants <TENANT_ID> [<TENANT_ID> ...]
    2) glance member-delete --images <IMAGE> [<IMAGE> ...]
                            --tenants <TENANT_ID> [<TENANT_ID> ...]

Change-Id: I77a9e0689c6af37f0e48b69a9ba34bdee2fc7e1e
Closes-Bug: #1221757

commit_message:
Fix inefficient transaction usage in floating_ip_bulk_destroy

floating_ip_bulk_destroy was creating a session, then not using it
while it iterated over given ip ranges. Instead, it was creating a new
session for both retrieving and deleting floating ips.

Because these updates now happen in a transaction, they must be
committed before calling the reservations api, which expects to be
able to see the changes.

Note that this function still races:

* between querying floating ips and deleting floating ips
* between populating project_id_to_quota_count and updating quota

It needs to be re-architected. This change simply makes the current
behaviour more efficient.

Change-Id: I25635eeb6c85f834f740d7b4501b2f4df773a258

Where and how are you going to use this?'}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2015-03-12 00:56:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yeah, um, I'm uncertain on this as proposal bot posts comments to all subscribed projects for requirements updates. I'm not sure we have a way of testing changes to the bot operations. I don't think we want to put ourselves in a position of spamming the projects by mistake."}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-03-12 04:14:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hmm, I didn't think *this* was going to be a controversial change (the linked follow-on, yes, but not this.)

To have a proposal bot like function for a project, digging through things, I think you need to have:
1) a repo
2) a projects.txt file at the root of that repo
3) a script in your repo at tools/sync-projects.sh (special-cased for requirements)
4) some hard-coded magic in the above script, that defines which repo and the gerrit review subject line
5) an infra jenkins job to run it all in the post queue

The *only* thing this review does is remove the need for the hard-coded magic in step 4, and allow that project specific goo to be defined in that project itself.

You still have to have all the rest, including a project-config defined jenkins job.

Notably, this change does not change *any* existing proposal bot behavior, nor does it add any new proposal bots."}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2015-03-23 23:07:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The controversialness is that we have "global" requirements and we should always be syncing from the global requirements. This subverts that. Additionally the global requirements should cover what you need already. This is just going to reinvent the wheel and break the global ness of our requirements.'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-03-23 23:23:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Oh, I know that part is controversial, but that's later patches.  This just allows not hard-coding some constants in this script; it has nothing to say as to what it's used for."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-29 14:05:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-04-29 21:54:45.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add version removal rule to stop discovery warning

Cinder recently added version discovery leveraging Keystone Client. For
cases where the service catalog still contains version numbers, this can
result in Keystone attempting to do discovery at the base url with the
version number and giving warnings. This will set a version removal rule
so Keystone can find the correct base url.

Change-Id: I71432468fea8bf1e50f180ab7f6dd69ee9aaa7e6
Closes-Bug: #1448244

commit_message:
Bump target release.

pbr's next release treats such conflicts as errors. We need to either
remove the manual version override, or have the version configured correctly.

Change-Id: I08ac1784b5dc88ab3bdb1b3b3cc89e97da96492c

commit_message:
Amphora SSH Driver

Adds config value to retrieve key for amphora access
Adds a HAProxyManager class with methods to modify/delete/start/stop an amphora
Modified sample_config to include amphorae on load balancer

Change-Id: I3fc2423a480ecc4b1b732a83fa1d4981c213da47
Implements: blueprint bp/haproxy-amphora-driver

commit_message:
Fix ArchiveTestCase on MySQL due to differing exceptions

Inserting a row without providing all required values raises
OperationalError rather than DBError when using a MySQL backend.

commit_message:
Enable filtering events on event_time

Currently, trying to filter on event time silently fails, the API
accepts the request but you get all events back.  This fixes that
problem and enables filtering on an exact match of a particular
event_time.

Change-Id: Idca18023678005b7f6f7c14d961fca579bd0cde0
Partial-Bug: #1444100

commit_message:
Fix ring data parser to allow for optional dispersion field

Swift was changed to add an option dispersion field to the output
of the swift-ring-builder command.  Also a line was added for the
overload factor, need to handle that as well.
Added a new spec for testing provider methods.

Change-Id: I1ae650e1514d69dc9c26b6054837f00fb4eb7bcb
Closes-Bug: #1444557

Stop deleting token prefixes when processing ENABLED_SERVICES negations

The old regex would convert "-q-lbaas,q-lbaasv2" into "v2".

(3 comments)

Jeff, this looks like a very good start for functional testing.

The "testenv" image looks fine to me, it's super simple which is good.
The "test_rabbitmq.sh" provides an easy enough example.

How do you plan to build the images to be tested? You can probably sort something out with "tools/build-all-docker-images" that accepts git revisions.

I also think you should create a fig config file specifically for testing purpose.

IMO, you should split this in separate commits, one for testenv image, another that adds support for building images to be tested, and plenty of commits to add functional tests.'}, {'account_id': 3098, 'date': '2015-03-06 22:25:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Lots of great feedback. The most important thing I think that much be worked out is the networking because I don't think I can use links after all..."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-03-09 18:54:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

--net=host is mandatory so host links are out.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-03-09 18:58:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't think it is necessary to create a separate heat VM environment for testing.  Instead lets just use the virtual machine we are given to build the container, start it, and run the test case.

Regards
-steve"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-24 14:33:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 3098, 'date': '2015-04-29 21:15:52.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Writing python tests are easier, running in a virtualenv is probably easier to debug and faster, so this has been superseded here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/168598/'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-06 06:41:39.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Add first functional test for Kolla

First test is written in bash, but start.sh in test container can easily
be extended to run a python test runner for python based tests. The test
container takes advantage of the compose link functionality to easily be
able to find the network address for a given service. Future services
will probably want to be queried via Keystone.

(WIP: I haven't created the testenv image due to possible renaming and
other potential incoming suggestions. The image in kollanode.yaml would
have to be changed. Had to remove net:host for link functionality.)

Change-Id: Ia7744e3b9755a5feca0c8e6be89c152a41e01567
"}]
commit_message:
WIP: Add first functional test for Kolla

First test is written in bash, but start.sh in test container can easily
be extended to run a python test runner for python based tests. The test
container takes advantage of the compose link functionality to easily be
able to find the network address for a given service. Future services
will probably want to be queried via Keystone.

(WIP: I haven't created the testenv image due to possible renaming and
other potential incoming suggestions. The image in kollanode.yaml would
have to be changed. Had to remove net:host for link functionality.)

Change-Id: Ia7744e3b9755a5feca0c8e6be89c152a41e01567

commit_message:
Only delete 'owned' packages for --exists-action update

Due to the fact that fqns are no longer unique update might currently
not work correctly, because it searches for package to delete by fqn.
To improve this situation this patch attempts to search for the package
in the current tenant and deletes it by id.
In case it is not found - raise the error, cause it most likely means
that the package is in another tennant and deleting it automatically is
dangerous.
This change relies on 'owned' parameter in api sorting, fixed
in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177796/

Change-Id: Iee04ea65f5c4937ded4e259e3c0cb64189801da2
Closes-Bug: #1448135

commit_message:
Fixes a config load bug for keystone v3 domains

The config loading code for keystone v3 authtokens
require domian paramters, but the keystone middleware
currently doesn't have those configuration options.
This fixes the config loading for the domains.

Change-Id: Ieb1571e64ef52b8e48fe21883d3c9f57c8402a54

commit_message:
Take advantage of better API filtering catalog filtering

* Removed client-side filtering, since API is now distincts
between catalog and manage requests
* Do not use owned=True for manage requests, since this is now the default
API behaviour.
* Simplify marker choice for next/prev links, since we reverse packages in
case of sort_dir='desc' to preserve visual order of apps.

Change-Id: I24b7a2b3f1f7fa0d093d336beb8430a05e56bdaf
Related-Bug: #1448226

commit_message:
Stop testing setup.py easy_install behaviour

Instead test pip install more thoroughly.

Also document that we don't support setup.py install's easy-install
behaviour.

Change-Id: I87872a69425f9d4f17047e584c12516508d57b16

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-10 17:51:31.000000000', 'message': "Fix sync-record failing with 500 error

Central's sync_record() method takes 5 arguments, but API's sync_record()
is calling it with 4 arguments.  Added the missing argument, recordset_id.

Additionally, the .gitreview file is pointing at the old
stackforge/designate.git GITHub repository.  Fixed it to point to the
correct GITHub repository, openstack/designate.git.

commit_message:
Fix sync-record failing with 500 error

Central's sync_record() method takes 5 arguments, but API's sync_record()
is calling it with 4 arguments.  Added the missing argument, recordset_id.

Additionally, the .gitreview file is pointing at the old
stackforge/designate.git GITHub repository.  Fixed it to point to the
correct GITHub repository, openstack/designate.git.

Change-Id: Ib5802dde470c856e91a42326cf902d2e6ed8beed
Closes-Bug: #1430455

move from bundler to chefdk

- deprecated Gemfile
- updated TESTING and README
- updated Rakefile to use chef exec instead of bundle exec
- refactored specs to work with new chefspec version

This patch adds a check in the Ironic driver to prevent it from destroying
the instance if the node has been put in maintenance mode. The maintenance
mode in Ironic is a flag to indicate that something went wrong with the
node and a operator should take a look at it, therefore we should not
have an external service trying to modify the states in the Ironic node.

Related-Bug: #1443374

'}]
commit_message:
Ironic: do not destroy if node is in maintenance

This patch adds a check in the Ironic driver to prevent it from destroying
the instance if the node has been put in maintenance mode. The maintenance
mode in Ironic is a flag to indicate that something went wrong with the
node and a operator should take a look at it, therefore we should not
have an external service trying to modify the states in the Ironic node.

Related-Bug: #1443374
Change-Id: Ifb69fddd0a595a4b9fceee37841a132c23c24968

commit_message:
Set root disk == node disk for puppet jobs

When using Puppet we don't want an ephemeral partition.
This patch configures the Puppet CI job such that the
ROOT_DISK is equal to the default NODE_DISK size
which means Ironic won't waste space on the ephemeral
partition.

This change will be important (required even) as we
expand the CI make use of things like Ceph which uses
/srv/data for its data storage by default... it would
be very easy to exceed the space on the root partition.

By simply making full use of the root disk we allow
project defaults to work seamlessly with our TripleO CI.

Change-Id: Icd85ed156fe167573cad976772c32bca1c84a04a

commit_message:
Disable dhcp_domain in Nova for the overcloud as well

The overcloud networking is managed by Neutron so we do not want
Nova to append its default domain part to hostnames.

Change-Id: Ic1edda158bf0579ed34455ad27db8ca444d26b85

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-28 09:33:22.000000000', 'message': 'Disable dhcp_domain in Nova so we do not append .novalocal

Given we enforce network management via Neutron, this change will
make sure Nova is not appending the .novalocal domain to the guests
hostname. Neutron is providing its own default domain part as well
(openstacklocal) via dhcp.

Change-Id: Iadfdf4120c4d1c9b6976321753957fd4eecf301c
'}]
commit_message:
Disable dhcp_domain in Nova so we do not append .novalocal

Given we enforce network management via Neutron, this change will
make sure Nova is not appending the .novalocal domain to the guests
hostname. Neutron is providing its own default domain part as well
(openstacklocal) via dhcp.

Change-Id: Iadfdf4120c4d1c9b6976321753957fd4eecf301c

commit_message:
[WIP] Add dr-agent service.

Add dr-agent service to devstack for the development of
BGP dynamic routing blueprint:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/bgp-dynamic-routing

To run the service just add

    enable_service q-dragent

at your local.conf file. This is WIP and is pushed to help BGP reviewers
to test the feature.

Change-Id: I9c6faa8b5b95017c6a35bba9c0a9269d8f95c8c3

commit_message:
Merge server shelve tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges servers shelve functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: I16c565dab63d385633d406021709cbd6f9ddbc63

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges suspend-server functional tests.

commit_message:
Merge flavor_access functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges flavor_acess functional tests.

In V2 flavor_access has following extensions
- os-flavor-access
- os-flavor-manage
- OS-FLV-DISABLED
- OS-FLV-EXT-DATA
- os-flavor-swap

Change-Id: Ie552312079233ddacf3fdce5903a11ba280be2fd

instead of skipping why not just remove the job?'}, {'account_id': 10224, 'date': '2015-04-14 19:00:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Lets assume that we have two projects A and B. Both of them don't use branches, and use stable-compat-jobs template to verify compatibility.

The template runs jobs against ver1 and ver2 stable versions.

Project A is restricted in global requirements of ver1, but isn't restricted in ver2. B isn't restricted at all.

In this case we cann't use the template for both projects. We can use it for B, but until it has been restricted in any stable version. But if we decide to remove the restriction from A, we will use the template again.

Thus don't have a one place with a set of stable versions. But we have to define stable versions checks for each such projects. And do not forget to reset all of them when a new stable branch is cut. For example at the moment no compat jobs are run against proposed/kilo if i'm not mistaken.

So i thought that the only point with the list of compatible versions is the best solution to manage versions, and we should keep it. But how to handle the case above? Only by skipping the job at run time. At least i didn't think out something else."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-04-14 20:05:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Sorry I don't follow your explanation. Perhaps giving an example will help."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-04-14 20:06:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

-1 since I am weary about having a job turn into a no-op automatically.'}, {'account_id': 10224, 'date': '2015-04-14 20:51:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Initially the idea was to continue to use stable-compat-jobs, which contains

 <job>-{name}-icehouse
 <job>-{name}-juno

, for all client projects to have something like:

 for pythonclient ("master" is 1.30)
 <job>-novaclient-icehouse: SKIPPED
 <job>-novaclient-juno: SKIPPED

 for glanceclient ("master" is 2.30)
 <job>-glanceclient-icehouse: SKIPPED
 <job>-glanceclient-juno: SUCCESS

 for cinderclient ("master" is 3.30)
 <job>-cinderclient-icehouse: SUCCESS
 <job>-cinderclient-juno: SUCCESS

 if global requirements have

 for icehouse
 novaclient<=1.20
 glanceclient<=2.20
 cinderclient>=3

 for juno
 novaclient<=1.25
 glanceclient>=2.25
 cinderclient>=3

 And when
glanceclient>=2.25,<=2.28
is added to global requirements, we automatically (with no
changes in project-config) have

 for glanceclient ("master" is 2.30)
 <job>-glanceclient-icehouse: SKIPPED
 <job>-glanceclient-juno: SKIPPED

 Also we still have a possibility to add <job>-{name}-kilo
to stable-compat-jobs only, not to each client project config.

But if such automatic handling isn't appropriate, i'll abandon this.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-04-14 21:42:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I am weary of doing this automatically.

Also if a repo is capped in g-r stable/* there is no need to check compatibility of master repo against stable/*. If said repo wants to backport a fix to stable/* it should create a stable/* branch itself.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-04-14 21:42:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

that being said it would be good to get a second opinion on this before abandoning or going forward with this.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-29 14:06:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

No one was interested in this last two weeks. All components resolved the bug by particular commits. Now there is no reason to make something common.'}]

commit_message:
Check global requirements before running of tempest-dsvm-neutron-src

{pipeline}-tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-{name}{branch-designator} is
designed to verify compatibility with stable releases for library or
client projects. But OpenStack global requirements in a stable release
can contain top restriction for a project version. E.g. Juno restricts
novaclient version up to 2.20. So there is no need to run this check.
Moreover DevStack either fails to start, or starts with an old client.

This patch set introduce a requirement check script (based on project-
requirements-chage script) and use it in {pipeline}-tempest-dsvm-
neutron-src-{name}{branch-designator} template to skip a job if global
requirement for a project is defined and a project version doesn't fit
it.

I'll re-check it when it seems happier."}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-04-28 16:44:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1 We agreed that we need a way to allow client-side translation to be done in HTML, much like how Django uses the "trans" function. Currently, the work-around is to use "gettext" in our Javascripts. This is undesirable because it pollutes our Javascript controller file with i18n strings. I am working on a solution that would allow Django makemessages to pick up translation in HTML as a filter. I'm not entirely it is possible but it is worth the investigation. Example usage: "hi" | hz-translate If the solution above works, we can migrate our i18n strings into the HTML templates directly. So long story short, if you convert your factory to a filter, it would align with this direction a bit more.'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-04-28 17:20:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Thai, I'll demonstrate what the factory is good for, but also implement the 'trans' filter. I had actually implemented one before but the thought then was that people were afraid that if I implemented it before message collection worked, it would cause confusion. But I'll set up the filter...that will be really nice! Thanks, Thai!"}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-04-28 17:55:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-04-28 17:58:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: As a quick example, please look at the 'trans' filter in filters.js. This uses the hz.i18n.gettext service (factory). You need a factory because other filters and javascript throughout the app will need to perform gettext-like functions. You COULD just use $filter to do this, but that would be clunky relative to using a standard injected function. Basically, locating the logic in a service is a good way of providing the service to any feature that needs it."}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-04-28 18:07:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (2 comments) Some nits.'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-04-28 18:13:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-04-28 18:15:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-04-28 18:18:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-04-28 18:31:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-28 19:21:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1 Build succeeded (check pipeline). - commit_message:
Add Angular service to provide translation

Adds a service that provides an injectable service wrapping the existing
translation mechanism.  This helps with testing and abstracts away the
particular translation mechanism.  Applying the use of this service would
allow the code to reduce implicit dependencies on globally-scoped items.

Change-Id: Iff4e66996760810adf4ba4ac1b63a86313a042ed
Partial-Bug: 1446739

Removed 'PYTHONHASHSEED=0' from tox.ini

from tox.ini

commit_message:
Changed logic in _compare_result  api_samples_test_base

json responses, could contain fields which values are
serialized json strings. to properly compare such embedded
jsons in _compare_result, added extra attempt to deserialize
string before comparison

Partial-Bug: #1348818

Change-Id: Ife379af619a9f1cf571aca3b1a09a7f453cef146

commit_message:
Fixed functional in tests_servers, to pass with random PYTHONHASHSEED

In tests/unit/image/fake.py get_valid_image_id returned random
image_id. This cause test assertion fails, as not all images,
that stored in fake has 'auto_disk_config': 'True'

Partial-Bug: #1348818

Change-Id: I900d6501bc57a23dc703bcfeef311e9c7707d584

commit_message:
Update the Vendor Passthru documentation

This patch updates the documentation about the Nodes and Drivers Vendor
Passthru. It talks about the discoverability of the vendor methods via
the Ironic API, the support for multiple HTTP methods and what to expect
of a asynchrounous or synchrounous method.

Change-Id: I6a3c971dfe53cc7148ea2a51c6449bf729d39fa5

commit_message:
allow DEVSTACK_DIRS to be overridden

Allowing DEVSTACK_DIRS to be overridden lets the run_resources.sh
script work outside of grenade. This is needed for the -d option added
in the last patch to actually do something useful.

Change-Id: Ic56e300a0ab1872e4cef37a22dd09cd4a8dd1e92

commit_message:
Fix failures for integration tests

These unit tests were affected by the lack of callback registration.

Callbacks can be wiped out depending on the order in which subscriptions
and mocking of the callback registry manager takes place. By subscribing
during setUp, this ensures that the integration is in place so that
tests can pass.

Closes-bug: #1448245

Change-Id: I0dfa1ffa39403cbe00d2724fe21e6e22ef77e07d

commit_message:
Make iptables firewall work with L3 plugin without DVR support

iptables firewall implementation expects 'distributed' attribute
is populated in router_info.router, but this attribute is only
populated when L3 plugin supports DVR extension. This commits
take into account the case where 'distributed' attribute does
not exist in router_info.router.

Change-Id: I2b0c208d74923f9ea0fc35bcea00e11152bbdb3d
Closes-Bug: #1448439
