commit_message:
Make the reaper use same timestamp for replica deletes

The account reaper is using a unique timestamp when deleting
replicas of the same resource. This will result in unnecessary
replication traffic after reaping.

This patch makes the reaper use a single timestamp per resource.

Probe test is modified to check that delete times are equal
across replicas before replicators run.

test_direct_client.py is modified to check that it uses explicit
timestamp when passed to direct_delete_[object|container]
methods.

Drive-by bug fixes in the probe test e.g. it was not sending
X-Backend-Storage-Policy-Index when doing a direct GET to check
object state, so the 404s being verified could in fact be due
to diskfile not existing rather than diskfile being deleted.

Closes-Bug: 1442879
Change-Id: I8bab22d66308bb9d3294e1e0def017c784228423

commit_message:
libvirt/utils.py: Remove 'encryption' flag from create_cow_image

Current code in create_cow_image inherits the 'encryption' property of a
qcow2 overlay from its backing file (also called base image).

However, importantly, even if the base image is encrypted, Nova has no
support for unencrypting it. So inherting the 'encryption' property
(from the backing file) serves no purpose. (Thanks Dan Berrange for
confirming this.)

Additionally, qcow2 encryption support is currently deprecated[1], with
plans[2] for a better future implementation, by upstream QEMU. Various
reasons (not least because of "flawed crypto") for it are noted in the
URL below, so it is reasonable to doubt if there are any serious users
of encyrpted images with its current design.

So, let's remove the 'encryption' flag from now.

[1] https://lists.gnu.org/archive/html/qemu-devel/2015-03/msg03433.html
    -- "block: Deprecate QCOW/QCOW2 encryption"
[2] https://www.berrange.com/posts/2015/03/17/qemu-qcow2-built-in-encryption-just-say-no-deprecated-now-to-be-deleted-soon/

Change-Id: If61ee881c21835e5d538d0eb12383b4b4ef2cfd4

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-28 07:16:56.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt/utils.py: Remove needless code from create_cow_image

The said code was added (but commented out) by this commit
51441e369bb05e9cb9149ac9a7290fe541e3ed1a, which hoped to inherit
'preallocation' (of qcow2 metadata) property of a qcow2 overlay from its
backing file.

I.e. if you create a base image with 'preallocation' option:

    $ qemu-img create -f qcow2 base.qcow2 1G -o preallocation=metadata

And, create an overlay with the above image as its backing file and
provide the 'preallocation' option:

    $ qemu-img create -f qcow2 -b ./base.qcow2 -F qcow2 \
               overlay.qcow2 -o preallocation=metadata

it results in the below error:

    "qemu-img: overlay2.qcow2: Backing file and preallocation cannot be
    used at the same time"

QEMU upstream source confirms that, it is indeed an invalid combination
This behavior has not changed since the feature to preallocate qcow2
metadata was introduced originally[1].

So, it is safe to remove the commented out code, which is trying to do

commit_message:
libvirt/utils.py: Remove needless code from create_cow_image

The said code was added (but commented out) by this commit
51441e369bb05e9cb9149ac9a7290fe541e3ed1a, which hoped to inherit
'preallocation' (of qcow2 metadata) property of a qcow2 overlay from its
backing file.

I.e. if you create a base image with 'preallocation' option:

    $ qemu-img create -f qcow2 base.qcow2 1G -o preallocation=metadata

And, create an overlay with the above image as its backing file and
provide the 'preallocation' option:

    $ qemu-img create -f qcow2 -b ./base.qcow2 -F qcow2 \
               overlay.qcow2 -o preallocation=metadata

it results in the below error:

    "qemu-img: overlay2.qcow2: Backing file and preallocation cannot be
    used at the same time"

QEMU upstream source confirms that, it is indeed an invalid combination
This behavior has not changed since the feature to preallocate qcow2
metadata was introduced originally[1].

So, it is safe to remove the commented out code, which is trying to do
supply an invalid combination of options to `qemu-img`.

[1] http://git.qemu.org/?p=qemu.git;a=commit;h=a35e1c17 --
    ("qcow2: Metadata preallocation", 17 AUG 2009)

Change-Id: I39a10c9c5a9e164cabff97292a53bf0023cfb43e

commit_message:
Give post queue normal priority

Right now publishing of documents to docs.openstack.org takes more than
3 hours - and that is quite long for getting everything ready and tested
for the kilo release.

Since we have the nodes, raise the priority again to normal.

Change-Id: I0497549ddf428ad3539b3afbe25a021a6780563a

[{'created': '2015-04-25 22:52:30.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt/utils: Remove workaround that inherits qcow2 'cluster_size'

Commit 51441e36 ("Inherit the base images qcow2 properties",
2012-SEP-17) introduced this behavior: when creating (using `qemu-img`)
a qcow2 overlay from a base image, it ensures that the overlay inherits
the 'cluster_size' value from the base image. Apparently, this was
introduced because (taking the hint from the to-be-removed code
comment), many moons ago the overlay image didn't seem to inherit.

Tried to reproduce this behavior with last three stable releases of
`qemu-img` (also the QEMU 1.2, the version released at the time above
Nova commit was introduced), to no avail. Test:

Create a base image, note its 'cluster_size':

  $ qemu-img create -f qcow2 base.qcow2 1G
  [. . .] cluster_size=65536 lazy_refcounts=off

Create an overlay based the base image, note its 'cluster_size':

  $ qemu-img create -f qcow2 -b ./base.qcow2 -F qcow2 overlay1.qcow2
  [. . .] cluster_size=65536 lazy_refcounts=off

As it can be noticed, the 'cluster_size' of the base and overlay images
match.

So, let's remove the workaround code, outdated TODO item and the expired
pastebin.

Change-Id: I6ffe6f7454383faac753709db7013380c91517da
'}, {'created': '2015-04-27 09:50:12.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt/utils.py: Cleanup create_cow_image function

The below commit:

    commit 51441e369bb05e9cb9149ac9a7290fe541e3ed1a
    Author: Joshua Harlow <harlowja@yahoo-inc.com>
    Date:   Mon Sep 17 16:42:33 2012 -0700

        Inherit the base images qcow2 properties

introduced this behavior: when creating a qcow2 overlay, using
`qemu-img` tool, the overlay image inherits certain properties like:
'cluster_size', 'encryption', 'preallocation' (though, this specific
option is commented out) from its backing file.

Speaking with a QEMU block layer developer, Kevin Wolf, he clarifies
that qcow2 overlay images do _not_ inherit properties from its backing
file -- all options to `qemu-img` command, when creating images need
to be specified _explicitly_.

So, let's remove the code (including outdated TODO item and an expired
pastebin) that inherits backing file properties since qcow2 overlay
images do not inherit (except for 'size' of the disk image, if it isn't
specified).

NOTES:

  - A default qcow2 'cluster_size' value of 65536 bytes (i.e. 64 KiB) is
    used when creating images.
  - Qcow2 encryption support is currently deprecated[1], with plans[2]
    for a better future implementation, by upstream QEMU. Various
    reasons (not least because of "flawed crypto") for it are noted in
    the URL below, so I doubt if there are serious users of encyrpted
    images with its current design.

[1] https://lists.gnu.org/archive/html/qemu-devel/2015-03/msg03433.html
    -- "block: Deprecate QCOW/QCOW2 encryption"
[2] https://www.berrange.com/posts/2015/03/17/qemu-qcow2-built-in-encryption-just-say-no-deprecated-now-to-be-deleted-soon/

Change-Id: I6ffe6f7454383faac753709db7013380c91517da

'}, {'created': '2015-04-28 07:16:56.000000000', 'message': "libvirt/utils.py: Clarify comment in create_cow_image function

The below commit:

    commit 51441e369bb05e9cb9149ac9a7290fe541e3ed1a
    Author: Joshua Harlow <harlowja@yahoo-inc.com>
    Date:   Mon Sep 17 16:42:33 2012 -0700

        Inherit the base images qcow2 properties

introduced the behavior: when creating a qcow2 overlay from a base
image, the overlay image inherits properties like 'cluster_size' from
its backing file.

Explanation about it in the comment was not clear and had a URL to an
expired pastebin. Reword the comment with details (also remove an
outdated TODO item and an expired pastebin).

Some related notes:

Speaking with a QEMU block layer developer, Kevin Wolf, he clarifies
that qcow2 overlay images do _not_ inherit properties from its backing
file (assuming it had a non-default 'cluster_size' value). I.e. when
creating images with `qemu-img` tool, all options to it need to be
explicitly specified (except for 'size' of the disk image, if it isn't
specified).

Cases where inheriting the 'cluster_size' of an overlay image from its
backing file might be useful (thanks Dan Berrange, for the below
discussion):

  - Qcow2 default cluster_size has changed in the past (last in June
    2009, for version 0.11 -- confirmed with QEMU upstream) so depending
    on what specific version of QEMU people use to create images they
    upload (to Glance), it might affect things.
  - People might use a particular cluster_size that is matching some
    aspect of their storage. (Though, in practise, this seems to be very
    rare and might be useful in some really special storage
    environments.)
     - NOTE: A (global) default qcow2 'cluster_size' value of
       65536 bytes (i.e. 64 KiB) is used by QEMU when creating qcow2
       images.

Change-Id: I6ffe6f7454383faac753709db7013380c91517da

commit_message:
libvirt/utils.py: Clarify comment in create_cow_image function

The below commit:

    commit 51441e369bb05e9cb9149ac9a7290fe541e3ed1a
    Author: Joshua Harlow <harlowja@yahoo-inc.com>
    Date:   Mon Sep 17 16:42:33 2012 -0700

        Inherit the base images qcow2 properties

introduced the behavior: when creating a qcow2 overlay from a base
image, the overlay image inherits properties like 'cluster_size' from
its backing file.

Explanation about it in the comment was not clear and had a URL to an
expired pastebin. Reword the comment with details (also remove an
outdated TODO item and an expired pastebin).

Some related notes:

Speaking with a QEMU block layer developer, Kevin Wolf, he clarifies
that qcow2 overlay images do _not_ inherit properties from its backing
file (assuming it had a non-default 'cluster_size' value). I.e. when
creating images with `qemu-img` tool, all options to it need to be
explicitly specified (except for 'size' of the disk image, if it isn't
specified).

Cases where inheriting the 'cluster_size' of an overlay image from its
backing file might be useful (thanks Dan Berrange, for the below
discussion):

  - Qcow2 default cluster_size has changed in the past (last in June
    2009, for version 0.11 -- confirmed with QEMU upstream) so depending
    on what specific version of QEMU people use to create images they
    upload (to Glance), it might affect things.
  - People might use a particular cluster_size that is matching some
    aspect of their storage. (Though, in practise, this seems to be very
    rare and might be useful in some really special storage
    environments.)
     - NOTE: A (global) default qcow2 'cluster_size' value of
       65536 bytes (i.e. 64 KiB) is used by QEMU when creating qcow2
       images.

Change-Id: I6ffe6f7454383faac753709db7013380c91517da

commit_message:
Fixes X509 keypair creation failure

Currently, the Subject created for the X509 certificate
is too long, resulting in exceptions and failing to
create the keypair.

This change shortens the Subject.
Unit test added to prove the issue's existence.

Issue found by: Andrey Kurilin

Co-authored-by: Andrey Kurilin <akurilin@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I7885c120ce81a22d416f806779bf9a12092d5040
Closes-Bug: #1447653

commit_message:
Remove GW metric and default GW for br-mgmt

Default GW for Admin network is now set to GW from Admin network
for non-default node network group if it is set. Default GW for
Admin network is set to Master node IP otherwise.
Default GW for Admin network is only set for nodes where br-ex is absent.

Related-Bug: #1437842
Related-Bug: #1442078
Change-Id: I4ef6415436afb380eb5da32bde2943699da3c3ef

Because ChefSpec::Runner is depricated

commit_message:
Add hooks for extra post-deployment config

Adds optional hooks which can run operator defined additional config on
nodes after the application deployment has completed.

Change-Id: I3f99e648efad82ce2cd51e2d5168c716f0cee8fe

Failing is fine for the sed command, so add a "|| true". Also use

Change-Id: I2cdcf155f583057fc56392ec44d8affffceafc9c

commit_message:
Fix publishdocs

publishdocs failed when there was no content in publish-docs/draft and
then did not publish any files.

Failing is fine for the sed command, so add a "|| true". Also use
"mkdir -p" to ignore errors if publish-docs already exists.

Change-Id: I2cdcf155f583057fc56392ec44d8affffceafc9c

commit_message:
Linuxbridge Agent with ML2: switch provider

Like we did in OVS agent when running ML2 plugin, we need to:
* use neutron_agent_linuxbridge provider to configure the right config file.

Closes-bug: #1426080
Change-Id: Icf7391563dbfcafb788d23b0367fba810a90fb48

Is this supposed to go into master or stable/kilo?  Right now it's going into the master branch, but Serg said that if we merged to the master branch, we should remove the cap on the version."}, {'account_id': 13962, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:36:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7225, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:37:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

This commit is intended for stable/kilo because we are fighting with issue in a murano gate for stable/kilo. 

But at the same time we have same issues in master branch: 
* python-muranoclient is not versioned properly
* requirements should not be installed forcefully

Just in stable/kilo forceful installation breaks gate, and don't break it in a master"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:38:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Why are we removing -U from the pip install line?  Isn't that the right thing to do here?"}, {'account_id': 7600, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:42:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 7600, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:42:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 7225, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:43:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Essentially keystoneclient does not have upper cap for stevedore library, and congress with -U forcefully installs latest python-keystoneclient through installing python-muranoclient. Latest keystoneclient installs stevedore 1.4.0 but Heat expects 1.3.0 and does not work with 1.4.0 at all 

-> Murano & Heat are not working at all in stable/kilo devstack 

TL;DR
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/062923.html'}, {'account_id': 7600, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:45:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:54:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

This is targeted at master, instead of stable/kilo.  I don't think we want to remove the -U from master."}, {'account_id': 7600, 'date': '2015-04-29 18:18:37.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

now i think that we shouldn't apply any changes in master of congress. we don't want -U and also putting a cap on python-muranoclient will prevent us from detecting problems early enough"}]

commit_message:
[WIP] Do not install python-muranoclient forcibly

Changed Change-Id to test patch in stable/kilo

* Put a cap on python-muranoclient requirement
* Get rid of -U flag which is used to install thirdparty-requirements.txt

Change-Id: Ic85e859f2ddad179d292ec30d11255d51a5b8260

commit_message:
Do not install python-muranoclient forcibly

* Put a cap on python-muranoclient requirement
* Get rid of -U flag which is used to install thirdparty-requirements.txt

commit_message:
Only delete 'owned' packages for --exists-action update

Due to the fact that fqns are no longer unique update might currently
not work correctly, because it searches for package to delete by fqn.
To improve this situation this patch attempts to search for the package
in the current tenant and deletes it by id.
In case it is not found - raise the error, cause it most likely means
that the package is in another tennant and deleting it automatically is
dangerous.
This change relies on 'owned' parameter in api sorting, fixed
in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177796/

Change-Id: Iee04ea65f5c4937ded4e259e3c0cb64189801da2
Closes-Bug: #1448135

commit_message:
Do not install python-muranoclient forcibly

* Put a cap on python-muranoclient requirement
* Get rid of -U flag which is used to install thirdparty-requirements.txt

Change-Id: I9567027b1f02f68bdd3a0130eec7a6050a5543dc
(cherry picked from commit fa6bd7837692ba365425640a1b0e6db04cb72ff9)

commit_message:
view hypervisor details rest api should be allowed for non-admins

The current call to show hypervisor is broken and expects the
user to have admin privileges always.It does not allow non-
admin users to view hypervisor details. This should be
controlled based on the rule defined in the policy.json rather
than have the permissions mandated programmatically. This bug
is caused due to regression and was working earlier.So the
changes proposed here is merely retaining the older behavior.
To ensure that this works as before, the context passed to the
db api layer is elevated so that it passes the requires_admin_
context check that is present in the db layer.

Change-Id: I50437788aac72608998cf9c24d4d562b1ff20301
Closes-Bug: 1447084

(9 comments)

I mainly -1 because ceph extras doesn't exist for RHEL7, so this won't work on RHEL7 / CentOS7 / Fedora21.

Also concerning Loics comment about CI. I'm currently working on adding support for additional OS releases, but that's alas not so straight forward.
The main issue is that the standard puppet vagrant boxes switched from "Sata Controller" inside of their boxes to "IDE Controller", so it's not straight forward.
The current approach is to remove the additional disks, and instead provide additional disks via file backed loopback devices.'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-02-17 17:14:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add EL7 support

If Fedora is 20 or more, CentOS / Red Hat 7, we want to install EPEL7.
Otherwise, we want to setup EPEL6 for backward compatibility with Fedora
19 and before, and CentOS / Red Hat 6.X and before.

Closes-bug #1422516
Change-Id: Iea9ed9cfdd9a70074257009a19533094769b2e9f

commit_message:
Allow env var REPO_OS to easily switch between platforms

Use a env var instead of manually editing repo files to use
centos.   This also makes it easy for new tools like, test-patch
to switch between the platforms.

Next step will be to allow REPO_DEVICE=  to easily
setup the network interfaces in the multi node cases.

I think env vars are a simple way to handle this, but we could also
consider an user config file ~/openstack-chef-repo.cnf.  Thoughts?

Change-Id: I82e82b35b51e08ff503fdb10fa1ce041c4be4af2

"}, {'created': '2015-04-28 21:13:19.000000000', 'message': 'Fix sort column for event-list with nested-depth

The non-nested-depth case can rely on the sort ordering from the
API response, but because we mangle together the response from
several event-list API calls in the nested-depth call, it's necessary
to ensure the sort ordering is correct by sorting on event_time.

Currently, we're sorting on the wrong column, because of the logic
which inserts a new column heading after we look up the index,
but switching to the right column still relies on the prettytable
sortby_index, which doesn't work with the "start" slice option,

later patch).

an easier step towards enabling marker/limit.

'}]
commit_message:
Fix sort column for event-list with nested-depth

The non-nested-depth case can rely on the sort ordering from the
API response, but because we mangle together the response from
several event-list API calls in the nested-depth call, it's necessary
to ensure the sort ordering is correct by sorting on event_time.

Currently, we're sorting on the wrong column, because of the logic
which inserts a new column heading after we look up the index,
but switching to the right column still relies on the prettytable
sortby_index, which doesn't work with the "start" slice option,
if you want post-sort slicing (such as will be required to make
--marker and --limit work with the --nested-depth option, in a
later patch).

So, instead, pre-sort the list before passing to print_list, which
solves the immediate problem of wrong sort order, and provides
an easier step towards enabling marker/limit.

Change-Id: Ifc6c8875cfdc58c0185fbffe7d00a45a598d67bd

commit_message:
moving from bundler to chefdk

- deprecated Gemfile
- updated Rakefile to use 'chef exec' instead of 'bundle exec'
- updated TESTING.md
- replaced Runner in specs with SoloRunner for new chefspec version
- initialized file_cache_path to make git_sync spec for docker work

Change-Id: I845c712f2d0d216d9d4a9d32c28ac4b03e96109a

move from bundler to chefdk

- deprecated Gemfile
- updated TESTING and README
- updated Rakefile to use chef exec instead of bundle exec
- replaces Runner by SoloRunner in specs

commit_message:
Set the master requirements to the head of stable/kilo

Most of master is transitioning to the liberty cycle, to allow us
to continue gating the service install versions is being set back
to the head of the stable/kilo branch. This should be updated once
all upstream OpenStack projects fully transition to Liberty.

Change-Id: I5a1d27c0e86a11ebe8d97b2e1a8dfef21cb5d6fd

commit_message:
Take advantage of better API filtering catalog filtering

* Removed client-side filtering, since API is now distincts
between catalog and manage requests
* Do not use owned=True for manage requests, since this is now the default
API behaviour.
* Simplify marker choice for next/prev links, since we reverse packages in
case of sort_dir='desc' to preserve visual order of apps.

Change-Id: I0136307e09695f49663779570cf23560521d9585
Depends-On: Ica031058d963246ff4d76e52cfc8b8b44d207c9a
Related-Bug: #1448226

I don't exactly remember why we added these lines. But I'm pretty sure they are related to ipxe. I mean we have several options in which bootloader to use (pxelinux, ipxe, grub, etc.). Currently, we use pxelinux and I don't know if we are happy with it (especially taking into account 200 nodes feature).  Using ipxe assumes a node sends two dhcp requests. And to prevent an infinite booting loop the second request contains dhcp ipxe option which allows dhcp server to distinguish this second request from the first one. And these to lines are exactly about this. 

I'm not against this patch but I'd like to make sure the author understands the meaning of removing these lines. Please, acknowledge my message and I'll give my +1."}, {'account_id': 7195, 'date': '2015-04-29 11:49:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Vladimir The current solution breaks some broadcom cards. The option you provided blocks GPXE enabled devices from booting due to the exclude line. I don't see how excluding gpxe devices allows some unspecific other devices to function. I've tested KVM, VirtualBox, Broadcom (affected and unaffected by the related bug), and I'm waiting on another HW lab to test again. Was it a specific virtualized env that was breaking that required this logic?"}, {'account_id': 3009, 'date': '2015-04-29 15:38:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Unfortunately, git blame leads to the commit without any valuable comments and I don't remember why this line appeared. commit_message:
Remove pxe-service flag in Cobbler and GPXE exclusion

These options block Broadcom BCM5720 cards from PXE
boot and are not necessary for provisioning.

Change-Id: I4c6520bca8549fe96264f25827bc1e534669b860
Closes-Bug: #1410280

commit_message:
Reconfigure default route

We have some roles which are deployed before vrouter deployment
due to we need to reconfigure default route after vrouter is ready.

Default route reconfiguration:
* add new configure_default_route puppet function
* add new configure_default_route task in post deploy
* add tests

Change-Id: I5db09111a9eecad058654e5463ffb13d077cee70
Closes-bug: #1444962

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-29 14:13:36.000000000', 'message': "[IBP]: fix 'udevadm trigger' hanging

After unblacklisting of udev rules fuel-agent calls
'udevadm trigger' followed by 'udevadm settle'.
'trigger' cause to re-process of completely all of udev events even
not related to block devices activities.
According to udev's event monitor it gets stuck on processing
network devices related events.

In order to avoid re-triggering of NICs, fuel-agent should use available
match for subsystem:
eg.: 'udevadm trigger --subsystem-match=block'

With subsystem match enabled, it always takes just 0.05-0.1s to complete.

Change-Id: I5537a30dc531469aa5bd5b7276628a27c461ddce
Closes-Bug: #1450007
"}]
commit_message:
[IBP]: fix 'udevadm trigger' hanging

After unblacklisting of udev rules fuel-agent calls
'udevadm trigger' followed by 'udevadm settle'.
'trigger' cause to re-process of completely all of udev events even
not related to block devices activities.
According to udev's event monitor it gets stuck on processing
network devices related events.

In order to avoid re-triggering of NICs, fuel-agent should use available
match for subsystem:
eg.: 'udevadm trigger --subsystem-match=block'

With subsystem match enabled, it always takes just 0.05-0.1s to complete.

Change-Id: I5537a30dc531469aa5bd5b7276628a27c461ddce
Closes-Bug: #1450007

commit_message:
Move keypair to standalone example

There was a keypair example in the Network, but keypair is
a compute service.  I think standalone keypair example would
be best.

Fix cinder-backup deployment issues

Currently, cinder-backup isn't getting deployed correctly.  This commit
fixes two of the known issues so that we correctly update cinder.conf
on the cinder_volume hosts and also update the
cinder_service_backup_program_name so we correctly deploy the init
script for cinder-backup.

Partial-bug: #1399386
Change-Id: I18551197d5f3e6349a22e13f989b4c38ad6030af

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-29 14:26:07.000000000', 'message': "Pmanager: fix 'udevadm trigger' hanging

After unblacklisting of udev rules pmanager calls
'udevadm trigger' followed by 'udevadm settle'.
'trigger' cause to re-process of completely all of udev events even
not related to block devices activities.
According to udev's event monitor it gets stuck on processing
network devices related events.

In order to avoid re-triggering of NICs, pmanager should use available
match for subsystem:
eg.: 'udevadm trigger --subsystem-match=block'

With subsystem match enabled, it always takes just 0.05-0.1s to complete.

Change-Id: Id40d12f8799033d22c3b87b9bf143fb3a6445484
Closes-Bug: #1450007
"}]
commit_message:
Pmanager: fix 'udevadm trigger' hanging

After unblacklisting of udev rules pmanager calls
'udevadm trigger' followed by 'udevadm settle'.
'trigger' cause to re-process of completely all of udev events even
not related to block devices activities.
According to udev's event monitor it gets stuck on processing
network devices related events.

In order to avoid re-triggering of NICs, pmanager should use available
match for subsystem:
eg.: 'udevadm trigger --subsystem-match=block'

With subsystem match enabled, it always takes just 0.05-0.1s to complete.

Change-Id: Id40d12f8799033d22c3b87b9bf143fb3a6445484
Closes-Bug: #1450007

commit_message:
Update iLO documentation for capabilities

This commit updates the iLO documentation with the
nova flavor examples for how the iLO capabilities
can be used for scheduling.
It also updates the documentation for automatic
boot ISO creation for iscsi_ilo driver.

Change-Id: I392d3e5d46b62fa195d176b54e150258880f061f

"Please do not -1 when asking a question. Only -1 when you know what you are doing" This isn't constructive.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-04-26 13:22:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Frankly it's a benign (almost pointless) change.  Just some code shuffle.  The fact that it prompted an overly dramatic "poor me I get -1's while doing real work to make OpenStack better" is somewhat laughable.  I'm intentionally giving a 0 vote to see if anybody even reads my comment, let alone responds to it.

For the record:
@Ivan
Your statement in the form of a question was absolutely fine, keep it up (at least on Cinder reviews)

@Julien
Please learn to treat others with a little respect, you nor anybody else is infallible or beyond reproach.  Comments like "Only -1 if you know what you are doing" is completely out of line.  Frankly I wish I had a reason to ask a question and provide a -1 just to stress the point; but like I said, the patch is kinda silly anyway.  And I would SOO enjoy you telling me "Don't do this unless you know what you're doing", that would make my day.

If you want to belittle folks and treat disrespectfully in other projects feel free but I'd prefer not to do that in Cinder at least.

@JoeG
Your opinion about Ivan's vote is just that "your opinion", valid, appreciated but certainly not the "law of the land".  Thanks for your input and viewpoint. 

I am confused however, that you then follow with "I'm not sure I agree with this" and site the EXACT same reason that Ivan stated (although he stated it in the form of a question).  Isn't the definition of "not agreeing" with a patch a -1?  

Frankly I'm completely indifferent on this patch.  I don't see any real benefit, but perhaps "I don't know what I'm doing".  If the method in timeutils is actually removed at some point, great, we'll come back around.  Or if Julien can provide something valid in the commit as to "why" besides it's dangerous and possibly misleading, maybe I'll care.'}, {'account_id': 2023, 'date': '2015-04-26 14:39:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

It unarguably makes the code more readable so even if deprecation is miles away there is no reason it shouldn't get pushed."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-04-26 17:52:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Hi John,

The fact that you are indifferent to this patch tells me that there might be a problem with how Oslo is considered in other projects. I'll discuss with our PTL and will get back to you.

Thanks for your feedback!"}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-04-27 00:56:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

@Julien
Thanks, to be clear what I'm indifferent about is moving before deprecation, or that the problem being solved is critical here.  So AFAIC I have no problem at all with changing this now, don't see the need to wait for deprecation in oslo first.

I appreciate your response.

@Saggi
Not sure about "clearly more readable", seems pretty darn close but with added path and args.'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-04-27 06:56:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2015-04-27 16:17:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: -Code-Review

Julien, I'm always fine with doing code more clear and unified. I'm one who voted for time representation across all APIs (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/159892/).

Merging any patch related to some -2'ed is a bit confused to me. So I always prefer to -1 patch which I'm not sure to get it landed. I'm always OK with change my vote to +1/+2 if my questions are answered.

Putting -1 or even -2 doesn't mean that this patch shouldn't be merged. It means that we need to make some more work on it: changing the code or the commit message, addressing comments and questions, etc. Sometimes we need to discuss it on a weekly meetings if changes could broke something: API backwards compatibility, packaging, etc.

Since strtime is not already deprecated in oslo_utils, we shouldn't hurry up with merging it. I mean that this patch is useful, but not in a top priority.

Also, we've got rules for merging code clean up patches: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/CinderCodeCleanupPatches

I leave a chance to merge it to out core team or to Jay Bryant, our OSLO Liaison. I'll be happy to +2/A+ it once patch to oslo_utils will be merged or +2'ed."}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-04-27 18:14:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-04-29 14:55:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-29 14:55:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

commit_message:
Leverage timeutils, drop strtime() usage

This patch remove some code that tried to parse time in different way by
leveraging timeutils instead. It also drops strtime() usage as it's
going to be deprecated in oslo_utils (see
I8b5119e64369ccac3423dccc04421f99912df733).

Change-Id: Icb2906ccd4b381f80064e0f1348fc64e389031dd

commit_message:
Make SSL settings configurable for Glance

This commit allows enabling SSL for glance-api and registry
endpoints by adding few new node attributes. Glance API and registry
configuration files are also modified to use these node attributes.

With these changes, users can easily enable SSL - both in secure and
insecure mode. However, it is user's responsibility to generate and
provide location of SSL certificate and its key.

Closes-Bug #1445773

Change-Id: I1d0f776efb392e058bc3dbf0ee5223512b60f584

commit_message:
Check if cookies has cfrtoken

Try to get cfrtoken atribute from cookies,
if we do not have such just try to login without it

Related-Bug: 1313662

The approved spec was mentioning a DictOfStrings as the typed field for the
image information but that can't work due to the nested properties dict
contained in the image information.

Instead, the proposal is to work on a new ImageMeta object which would
basically propose https://review.openstack.org/#/c/76234

Previously-Approved: Kilo
"}]
commit_message:
Amend RequestSpec blueprint by using an ImageMeta object

The approved spec was mentioning a DictOfStrings as the typed field for the
image information but that can't work due to the nested properties dict
contained in the image information.

Instead, the proposal is to work on a new ImageMeta object which would
basically propose https://review.openstack.org/#/c/76234

Change-Id: I440632043aeb72b1f2e585c3c12caed089ffcefa
Previously-Approved: Kilo

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I75e6e15d50ef9830d0581efd4cbcceb3e626f7b7

commit_message:
Fixed incorrect version of PciDeviceList.

After change I8e2a9bd3bfa049bc099a15df3a14ad84e35ac372
we forgot to change version of PciDeviceList to 1.2
Also, versions of Instance, BlockDeviceMapping, FixedIp and
FloatingIp were updated because of dependence.

Change-Id: If8c526e1c34cc3d28694d7ebb125c7f74d80feea

commit_message:
Use ipv4 subnet in Heat scenario tests

Previously we used first subnet from network and it was correct, because
there was only one subnet in network by default. According to the last changes
in devstack new ipv6 subnet was added to the all default networks.
This patch adds function to the base class, which allows to choose
subnet based on ip version. All scenario tests were updated to use only ipv4
subnet.

Also was added property for FIP, which specify ip of vip.

Change-Id: I199075909b97fe98e1a3c1d175b0b4cf7100403d
Closes-Bug: #1449896

commit_message:
Add support for forcing migrate_flavor_data

In some cases it might be helpful to force the migration of flavor
data. For example, when operating on a snapshot of a production
database there may be instances in an operating state that would
stop the migration from finishing. Blocking on this will make it
impossible to finish the migrations (once the migrations require
all the data has been migrated).

Change-Id: I4f6c0679b144897f2bfc2fa06bc7c72b25a85fd3

commit_message:
Associate floating IPs with first v4 fixed IP if none specified

In the absence of a specified fixed address with which to associate a
floating IP, the first IPv4 address on the port should be associated.
Without the check for IPv4, IPv6 ports can be associated with a (IPv4)
floating IP, which is not supported.

Change-Id: Ib66a9109cc1c7999474daca5970d0af1f70886e4
Closes-Bug: 1437855

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I977248bec9560bcd730efe6bed741f1dc025fdf3

commit_message:
Include neutron_url_timeout in nova.conf

This change adds an attribute for neutron_url_timeout and a
corresponding parameter in the nova.conf template.

The default, 30 seconds, is the default used by nova if the parameter isn't
set.

Change-Id: Ie64c549ae4fc8bffeeced0e6c1d298c8faf29d31

commit_message:
Allow to use network label in nova_fixed handler format

Nova notifications provide network label per fixed_ip in create
payloads. This change updates code to allow nova_fixed handler format
to use the key "label" providing network label. The format:

 %(instance_name)s.%(label)s.%(domain)s

returns the fqdn:

 instanceXX.netYY.domainZZ

for instanceXX on netYY with domainZZ as nova_fixed handler domain.

Change-Id: I7ffef6464ab5e8e8f1e74dca8fcff972c2ad6d58
Closes-Bug: #1446242

commit_message:
Fixed rules for Congress integration tests

The root cause of the problem is incorrect rules which created for
Congress component in setUpClass function.
Rules stored in file rules_murano_system.txt
This patch adds additional rule to get environment id
(Using old rules for Murano)

Change-Id: I4e43a46f897fba271c06ee030ffc8f8f373d092a
Closes-Bug: #1449802

commit_message:
Fixed rules for Congress integration tests

The root cause of the problem is incorrect rules which created for
Congress component in setUpClass function.
Rules stored in file rules_murano_system.txt
This patch adds additional rule to get environment id
(Using old rules for Murano)

Change-Id: I4e43a46f897fba271c06ee030ffc8f8f373d092a
Closes-Bug: #1449802

repositories for new Fuel versions to make them
smaller. However, this technique contradicts
our current upgrade/patching approach. So, this
patch removes this functionality.

Related-Bug: #1446293

commit_message:
Remove differential (diff) repos

We used to create differential Ubuntu and Centos
repositories for new Fuel versions to make them
smaller. However, this technique contradicts
our current upgrade/patching approach. So, this
patch removes this functionality.

Closes-Bug: #1447135
Related-Bug: #1446293

Change-Id: I6c9288e77c6ccc5872056a8119230ec725846bba

Fix order of API operation listing

Fix some APIs to add missing methods
Fix name of WADLs to match resource names
Add introduction that describes order of operations
on the page
Correct resource names in section titles
Updated commit message to remove bug - that bug
was fixed through other changes

commit_message:
Add a dummy parameter for HAProxy resource

HAProxy resource supports reload operation but currently Pacemaker doesn't use
it if one of the unique parameters is changed. It was discovered that
a resource needs at least one parameter marked as unique=1.
Adding such dummy parameter to keep all current parameters unchanged and solve
the problem.

Change-Id: I54b7f838c9592736e61d997d30a15497e5c31604
Closes-bug: #1448160

commit_message:
Remove deprecated methods in VNX driver

This change amis to do a cleanup in VNX driver to remove those
deprecated methods.

commit_message:
Add Http Request Scenario

* (Ñheck-random-request) Add Multiple Http request scenario which
takes as input a list of Requests and compares response of random
picked request from the list with the expected Response.

* (Ñheck-request) Improve flexiblity of check-response scenario and
rename check-response to check-request.

Co-Authored-By: kumar rishabh <shailrishabh@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Roman Vasilets <rvasilets@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Id70935616c013271392219b1e642b5b87ddb4b9c

commit_message:
Use labels for virtual media dev in Ironic ramdisk

This commit changes Ironic deploy ramdisk to find out
the virtual media device by using labels instead of
looking at the model of block device.  This helps in
finding out the device irrespective of the hardware.
Corresponding Ironic change is
If5b78d9af7048f2631d050ee5ce01ab7a67e2354.

Closes-Bug: #1429340
Change-Id: I5e8a706989bad13051eb47db0b1e762e6c672318

commit_message:
packages/deb: fix target dependencies so make -j works again

Both repocleanup.done and reprepro.done targets
 - modify the local copy of MOS repo (which is a bad idea),
 - depend on ubuntu/mirror.done target

As a result two instances of reprepro try to concurrently modify the same
APT repo (which fails). Make repocleanup.done depend on reprepro.done to
avoid the problem.

Closes-Bug: #1449723
Change-Id: I283f4f10f9e1b43eb8a30cb9458a3443cc614e23

commit_message:
[IBP] turn off firewall on centos

Firewall should be disabled as it makes no sense to configure it as
FUEL will override network settings in a matter of seconds.

Change-Id: I9c7fbe3e129efa536dd9104341dabb6a384229f9
Closes-Bug: #1441136

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Initialize RabbitMQ on bootstrap node first

Generally there can be problems with starting RabbitMQ on all nodes at
the same time -- it might fail to initialize and start. We now
initialize RabbitMQ on the bootstrap node first in step 1 and on the
other nodes in step 2. See the linked bug and discussion [1] for more
info.

[1] http://rabbitmq.1065348.n5.nabble.com/Rabbitmq-boot-failure-with-quot-tables-not-present-quot-td24494.html

Closes-Bug: #1443426
Change-Id: I94790db483ab1ef3b27cf8a9543ff3d78efb9e06

commit_message:
Creation of subdomains and filtering by parent_id

* Creation of subdomains passing a parent_id from an existing domain
* list sub_domain requesting the list_domain call filtering by the
  parent_id

Implements bp reseller

Change-Id: I618e62a91030b5634b9aaa36a01da4815906295f

i am welcoming any idea someone might have...

also the only way to make that work is to keep the L2 Agent in the compute node (which i don't think we want..).

I don't think that OVS can connect to two different controllers (only as a redundancy measurement) that simultenously configure flows to it, or can it?"}, {'account_id': 15289, 'date': '2015-04-20 17:17:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> I don't think that OVS can connect to two different controllers (only as a redundancy measurement) that simultenously configure flows to it, or can it?

OVS can do that, and it can be useful if the two controllers coordinate with each other."}, {'account_id': 15289, 'date': '2015-04-20 17:37:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> I will check the suggested OVS driver in neutron, the main issue here is that we are now adding flows into a pipeline that is suppose to be managed by ovn-controller alone.
> I am not sure if this is a good idea, but i will check the code.

ovn-controller should be the only OpenFlow controller in charge of OVS in an OVN hypervisor.

> i am welcoming any idea someone might have... And adding Ben here for his thoughts regarding the modelling and what is actually going to be supported inside OVN.

OVN should be able to handle any of the models mentioned.  Are you looking for more specific feedback?'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-04-21 00:02:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
API calls to Registry now maintain Request IDs

Previously, glance-api calls to glance-registry did not include the
req-UUID request ID in that call. Instead a single call to glance-api
used separate request IDs for api and registry, leading to some
difficulty in traceback, debugging, and tracking bugs going into
glance and into registry.

Previous example log in glance-api:
2015-04-21 07:25:10.359 126050 DEBUG glance.registry.client.v1.client
[req-f2abec73-7a8c-4c5a-bded-f5eb82d627e4 5fca8fda352e46c7a006d4bf8083ab
be 00eb1978c3394438b8988cd8a755f128 - - -] Registry request GET /images/
05454482-f448-424b-ba9d-49d44a5af9fb HTTP 200 request id req-req-2433213
e-76c2-4ce3-95b6-d0db6cc8bdd0 do_request /opt/stack/glance/glance/
registry/client/v1/client.py:131

Updated example log in glance-api:
2015-04-21 07:27:33.057 126165 DEBUG glance.registry.client.v1.client
[req-1787ffe1-0537-4357-a735-18412292434d 5fca8fda352e46c7a006d4bf8083ab
be 00eb1978c3394438b8988cd8a755f128 - - -] Registry request GET /images/
05454482-f448-424b-ba9d-49d44a5af9fb HTTP 200 request id req-req-1787ffe
1-0537-4357-a735-18412292434d do_request /opt/stack/glance/glance/
registry/client/v1/client.py:131

Now, when glance-api calls glance-registry, the api request_id is passed
to registry. This helps to maintain the request ID for api and registry
when user makes a single call to api.

Change-Id: I871c1c17aca9af291598279db1d4057e217b4256
Closes-Bug: #1336958

[TBS3] Slight style fixes

* Removed bullets in Deploy Changes dialog warning list
* Added more space between items in Deploy Changes dialog warning list
* Diagnostic Snapshot link has more left margin
* Fixed node renamimg, it doesn't call an additional render now
* Fixed spaces on Welcome page

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-23 15:08:51.000000000', 'message': "Sync oslo service module for SIGTERM exit

oslo:service.py had some code where the child process would catch the
SIGTERM from the parent just so it could exit with 1 status rather
than with an indication that it exited due to SIGTERM. When
shutting down the parent doesn't care in what way the child ended,
only that they're all gone, so this code is unnecessary.

Also, for some reason this caused the child to never exit while
there was an open connection from a client. Probably something
with eventlet and signal handling.

This also requires we pull in eventlet_backdoor.

Syncs commit: 702bc569987854b602ef189655c201c348de84cb

commit_message:
Sync oslo service module

This does a full sync of the oslo.service module.  Note
that we've cherry picked some critical bug-fix changes
to this module already, this commit just syncs the full
module properly and gets us up to date where we should be.

Current HEAD in OSLO:
-----------------------
commit:  d5edda00b4eca65d57f94bd0ac1b790e6d1f732e
Date:    Wed Apr 22 19:49:00 2015 +0000
Merge "service child process normal SIGTERM exit"

Changes merged with this patch:
---------------------------------
d5edda00 - Merge "service child process normal SIGTERM exit"
702bc569 - service child process normal SIGTERM exit
64b5819e - Revert "Revert "Revert "Optimization of waiting subprocesses
           in ProcessLauncher
f5646edc - Revert "Revert "Optimization of waiting subprocesses
           in ProcessLauncher
d23b6589 - Revert "Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher"
593005b7 - ProcessLauncher: reload config file in parent process on SIGHUP
f29e865d - Store ProcessLauncher signal handlers on class level
bf92010c - Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher

NOTE: Commit 702bc569 was actually pulled in with commit d73ac96d .
      We shouldn't have merged that individual commit.  I include the
      commit here to document Oslo level that the service module is at
      cumulatively between that commit and patch.

Change-Id: I613ba5ba442cf533c0f68d06281d117fbac20bd6

commit_message:
Split validation.file_exists, allow `required' arg

Split validation.file_exists into `_file_access_ok' function.
Add validation argument `required' that specifies whether the file name
value is required to be non-None.

Change-Id: Ic86b92364482e7765e55d45b60749f532bbd78e1
Implements: blueprint vm-workloads-framework

commit_message:
Updates for Kilo release

Many small updates to various sections to:
* remove/reword/redirect old pre-icehouse cruft
* update links from Juno to kilo (eg config reference)
* generally improve anything that looked dated

Change-Id: I26618be8527cccc1cbb7811272613da7d410fe50

[CDH] swift lib support

Currently we have add swift lib jar into the DIB, so the cluster need
not to download the lib jar from outside repo

Closes-bug: #1443806

Fixing action_executions API

 * From workflow-executions are removed from list
 * Added 'task_name' attribute to resource (for further
   fetching it in CLI)

commit_message:
Update ops guide to Kilo release

This patch addresses various sections that referred to releases
Juno and earlier, and removes them or edits them to be up-to-date.

As debian was removed from the install guide this cycle, references
to the debian install guide have also been removed here.

Change-Id: If616c2af0f9e9f79e7c74c37e5f82994bb8b26a2

lu, one way to rebase off of my patch would be to use the download link[1] on that review to create a local branch that mirrors my patch. then rebase your patch on the original. if you would like i can rebase this patch.

the rebase button on a review allows you to rebase the patch to the current master.

so, the process would roughly be:

1. git fetch .... (from the link in [1])
2. git checkout -b base_patch
3. git checkout new_patch
4. git rebase -i base_patch

i hope that makes sense =)

commit_message:
Modified help display format to present a more user-friendly display

The current -h/--help display uses original cliff format,
the display is unfriendly due to mismatched indent.

This patch replaces the original HelpAction and formatter
imported from cliff with custom ones to present a more
user friendly display. And it is also more similar with
other OpenStack projects' help display.

Change-Id: I28405e4001369614f02ad755c12b138713e6c3b2
Closes-Bug:#1449516
(cherry picked from commit f73760f79757f88ee672dbd35de6443742c9d501)

commit_message:
Delete requirement on unneeded arguments

 * There was a requirement - mistralclient doesn't
 init without user_id or username and project_id or project_name
 However, keystone doesn't need this parameter if token is provided.

Closes-Bug: #1407992

Change-Id: I903d52f2552d6b5e718d13d5957404e0a2d9f9d3
(cherry picked from commit d339608bc1cb271ccabf4f5980c9cfbda3c4f1fb)

Hi Sergey,

Can you explain why you think we need to do the double bump here? You can't rewrite history, which means anyone with the older code on a compute node will have the version of the object that was defined when the error was first committed. commit_message:
Fixed incorrect version of FloatingIp object.

In change I34ec32f0b3704b01aaca9c0cb2b34eb6d3107513
Tag and TagList objects were added to the Instance object.
Because of this versions of Instance, BlockDeviceMapping
and FixedIP were updated. But version of FloatingIp wasn't
updated. It should be updated because it depends on FixedIp.

Also in change I4dff5267902362057cc5ee18357539b7192782cb
version of FixedIP object was updated but version
of FloatingIP object wasn't. Because of this we have to
update version of FloatingIP twice.

Change-Id: Icc881c8ef7158055d9287ef744021c1028737ff0

Sounds useful, but I still have concerns about the amount this seems to overlap with osprofiler.  According to the osprofiler readme, it intends to be able to collect data on db calls, and it has a middleware for hooking in to api requests.  I can't believe there isn't some way to have it only show you the profiling data from a single service instead of all the nested api calls, and if there isn't then that's probably something that should be added anyway.  It also claims you can send samples directly to a file if you don't want to use ceilometer.

Basically this feels to me like an extension to osprofiler, possibly to make it easier to use for db profiling, rather than a whole new thing by itself."}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-01-01 19:23:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Osprofiler is more common and better solution for this, take a look at github.com/stackforge/osprofiler


This is real sample: https://boris-42.github.io/ngk.html'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-01-01 19:25:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-01-23 15:06:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Boris, Ben,

Can OSProfiler be dropped directly into say the existing DSVM jobs? What else needs to be installed/configured/run? (is Ceilometer a hard dependency? for example).

On the other side, other than the choice of Implementation is there other concerns on the spec?'}, {'account_id': 9569, 'date': '2015-04-29 12:48:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Fixed a problem with incorrect size of storage in Admin/Hypervisors

Since using Ceph for ephemeral storage it adds up the ceph
storage seen in each storage node rather than just using
the real amount of ceph storage.
More information in bug description.

Closes-bug: #1387812

Change-Id: Ie2796a7dce2691213ac4a832fe2e688e8ddc7223

commit_message:
fix git_timed retry logic

git_timed retry logic actually only retried *if* we timed out, not if
the command itself failed, as it would explicitly exit if the return
code was anything except 124. This loops in all failure cases, which
was the intent of the original fix.

Related-Bug: #1282876

Change-Id: I576df4832665beb21992ffa873da28a198018530

There is definitely a bug here, there is a race with soft reboot and the libvirt handle_lifecycle_event stuff in the compute manager.  I have a log with a recreate from juno, just need to get the bug reported with details.

We don't do a good job of testing soft reboot with stress in the gate so I'm not surprised this is a problem.

The guy that recreated it internally is doing a stress test of soft rebooting 90 instances at once across 3 separate compute nodes, it must be too much on the system and it slows down the libvirt eventing stuff which causes the delay and race to shutdown the instance after it's been soft rebooted."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-11 01:48:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I want the option because this functionality is not tested well at scale, but I don't think that's really something we want to throw into the config option help.

This is basically a back door to disable a feature if it becomes troublesome in your environment - we seem to have a billion config options for things that are much less risky than this."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-15 01:03:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Another related bug:

https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1408176/comments/2

If you have running instances, restart libvirtd, it will stop the guests which triggers the event to stop the instances and sets vm_state=STOPPED, then on restart of libvirtd it will send the started event which nova will interpret as a problem since the instance vm_state is stopped and will shutdown the instance again.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-15 18:29:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Reported bug 1444630 for the newish related wrinkle.'}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2015-04-17 09:15:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

[{'created': '2015-02-25 22:20:15.000000000', 'message': 'Add config option to disable handling virt lifecycle events

Historically the _sync_power_states periodic task has had the potential
for race conditions and several changes have been made to try and
tighten up this code:

cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8
aa1792eb4c1d10e9a192142ce7e20d37871d916a
baabab45e0ae0e9e35872cae77eb04bdb5ee0545

The handle_lifecycle_events method which gets power state change events
from the compute driver (currently only implemented by the libvirt
driver) and calls _sync_instance_power_state - the same method that the
_sync_power_states periodic task uses, except the periodic task at least
locks when it's running - expands the scope for race problems in the
compute manager so cloud providers should be able to turn it off.

This is consistent with the view that Nova should manage it's own state
and not rely on external events telling it what to do about state
changes. For example, in _sync_instance_power_state, if the Nova
database thinks an instance is stopped but the hypervisor says it's
running, the compute manager issues a force-stop on the instance.

Also, although not documented (at least from what I can find), Nova has
historically held a stance that it does not support out-of-band
discovery and management of instances, so allowing external events to
change state somewhat contradicts that stance and should be at least a
configurable deployment option.

DocImpact: New config option "handle_virt_lifecycle_events" in the
           DEFAULT group of nova.conf. By default the value is True
           so there is no upgrade impact or change in functionality.

Change-Id: I26a1bc70939fb40dc38e9c5c43bf58ed1378bcc7

commit_message:
Add config option to disable handling virt lifecycle events

Historically the _sync_power_states periodic task has had the potential
for race conditions and several changes have been made to try and
tighten up this code:

cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8
aa1792eb4c1d10e9a192142ce7e20d37871d916a
baabab45e0ae0e9e35872cae77eb04bdb5ee0545
bd8329b34098436d18441a8129f3f20af53c2b91

The handle_lifecycle_events method which gets power state change events
from the compute driver (currently only implemented by the libvirt
driver) and calls _sync_instance_power_state - the same method that the
_sync_power_states periodic task uses, except the periodic task at least
locks when it's running - expands the scope for race problems in the
compute manager so cloud providers should be able to turn it off. It is
also known to have races with reboot where rebooted instances are
automatically shutdown because of delayed lifecycle events that the
instance is stopped even though it's running.

This is consistent with the view that Nova should manage it's own state
and not rely on external events telling it what to do about state
changes. For example, in _sync_instance_power_state, if the Nova
database thinks an instance is stopped but the hypervisor says it's
running, the compute manager issues a force-stop on the instance.

Also, although not documented (at least from what I can find), Nova has
historically held a stance that it does not support out-of-band
discovery and management of instances, so allowing external events to
change state somewhat contradicts that stance and should be at least a
configurable deployment option.

DocImpact: New config option "handle_virt_lifecycle_events" in the
           DEFAULT group of nova.conf. By default the value is True
           so there is no upgrade impact or change in functionality.

Related-Bug: #1293480
Partial-Bug: #1443186
Partial-Bug: #1444630

Change-Id: I26a1bc70939fb40dc38e9c5c43bf58ed1378bcc7

Remove py33 tox target.

Python 2.7 and 3.4 are the supported versions and we should not
indicate otherwise.

commit_message:
Explicitly say when job times out

When timeout -s 9 times out it has a return code of 137. Make the
output easier a little easier to understand by explicitly stating the
job timed out.

Change-Id: If986bdb64630d7ab2f3510f6a704fec858421612

commit_message:
add convenience tools

The following are some convenience tools that I created during grenade
refactor which might make sense in the tree. These make working on grenade
much easier.

cache_git.sh builds a local git mirror so you can set
GIT_BASE=/opt/git and iterate faster.

run_resource.sh <project> <phase> - lets you run resource test scripts
the way we'll run them in grenade for iterative development.

Both scripts include help with '-h' on their usage.

Change-Id: I997c3bfee09dab93ecaa52dd9b86d7811c63bfa3

commit_message:
make the ss debug include all services

When things fail to shut down look for open sockets to all services
not just keystone, this seems to be a problem with more projects.

Change-Id: I003115e72a29e4c7f201ef2017795ace6a885ead

commit_message:
Changed timeout value in test_001_services_state test

Changed duration in test description.
Sometimes it tooks more time to update nova services state on slow environment.
120 seconds must be enough.
Closes-Bug: #1449995

Change-Id: I934ed7e1fddfb847d201913f8cea10c2a1fc943c

commit_message:
Modified help display format to present a more user-friendly display

The current -h/--help display uses original cliff format,
the display is unfriendly due to mismatched indent.

This patch replaces the original HelpAction and formatter
imported from cliff with custom ones to present a more
user friendly display. And it is also more similar with
other OpenStack projects' help display.

Change-Id: I28405e4001369614f02ad755c12b138713e6c3b2
Closes-Bug:#1449516

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I1fd9eba88ec8d436f6d2e37df851dbaa84a8c78c

[{'created': '2015-04-20 10:14:49.000000000', 'message': "Delete requirement on unneeded arguments

 * There was a requirement - mistralclient doesn't
 init without user_id or username and project_id or project_name
 However, keystone doesn't need this parameter if token is provided.

Closes-Bug: #1407992

Change-Id: I903d52f2552d6b5e718d13d5957404e0a2d9f9d3
"}]
commit_message:
Delete requirement on unneeded arguments

 * There was a requirement - mistralclient doesn't
 init without user_id or username and project_id or project_name
 However, keystone doesn't need this parameter if token is provided.

Closes-Bug: #1407992

Change-Id: I903d52f2552d6b5e718d13d5957404e0a2d9f9d3

commit_message:
Adding script for retrieving OpenStack action list

 * It is simple CLI tool.
 * Script now works fine for: Nova, Keystone,
   Glance, Heat and Cinder.
 * in case of Keystone, user must provide full
   auth_info and use v3 auth_url.

TODO:
 * Think on optimal way to do it for neutron.

Change-Id: I3ed144bd84a6fbd24dc518c17cd3962bf3af4caa

commit_message:
Drop usage of keystoneclient

The keystoneclient cli is now deprecated and will soon be removed so use the
openstack client instead.

Change-Id: Id902647966bfce62cc8dce9802e34ef80390122d

commit_message:
Fix syntax error in apt.conf.d/03force-ipv4

Since Idc40f2ccf9fb8494b9b30c58775b38d9487ddcd4 we have a regression, so
native ubuntu provisioning (debian installer) isn't working properly and
after provisioning the nodes are hanged and unable to boot.

That's happened due to syntax error in apt configuration so apt fails to
install grub and other packages.

Closes-Bug: #1447696

Change-Id: I290717e264503c13b0d62bad21d57f89482396d3
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
project-config: Merge lint jobs (2/2)

Since both pep8 and bashate are voting, we can merge the two lint
targets into the "common" pep8 lint target. There's no need for a
separate bashate run.

This change is the second part for this.
Since the jobs are changed, we can now remove the obsolete bashate
tox.ini target.

Change-Id: I572ba3fe8b3a9a05f5239a858d2f701bfd8f684d

Since you separate it from another project, do you really want to loose all history? You can also import a filtered version of the existing repository and thus keep the history'}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2015-04-13 01:10:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks for your comments.

Yes, it's OK to us. We just have a code snapshot uploaded onto stackforge in the old project, no useful history."}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2015-04-13 02:52:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Wouldn't it make more sense to rename the project?"}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2015-04-13 03:08:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

You mean rename existing zvm-driver to neutron-zvm-plugin?

The background is:
There's an existing project - zvm-driver on StackForge, which contains
both nova-zvm-virt-driver and neutron-zvm-plugin. In order to make it
easier to develop, maintain and setting up CI system on StackForge,
we plan to create new projects on StackForge for each
nova-zvm-virt-driver and neutron-zvm-plugin, then obsolete project
zvm-driver.

Currently, stackforge/nova-zvm-virt-driver has been created.

My next plan is to create stackforge/neutron-zvm-plugin, then rename stackforge/zvm-driver to stackforge-attic/zvm-driver.

Could you suggest me a best way to do the change?"}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2015-04-15 06:16:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Huang,

It might be useful to try and preserve some of the history. My recommendation would be to arrange the existing nova-zvm-virt-driver and neutron-zvm-plugin parts into their own subtrees inside of the current zvm-driver project. Then I would create two new projects from these subtrees to preserve their history have them seed the split repositories.

You can find some information on splitting a repository here if you're interested: https://help.github.com/articles/splitting-a-subfolder-out-into-a-new-repository/

Cheers,
Josh"}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2015-04-15 09:11:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

Thanks a lot for your comments.
Work in progross on this.'}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2015-04-17 08:01:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Workflow

I have made a new neutron-zvm-plugin git repo with using "git filter-branch" in my local already.

If my understanding is correct, the new project stackforge/neutron-zvm-plugin should be created at first, then I can go ahead to push my local neutron-zvm-plugin with rewrite history info into the new project.

So would you please continue to review this change at first to create the new project?

Thanks
Rui'}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2015-04-20 05:33:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Huang,

That requires force pushing straight into the repo and not via gerrit (afaik) which doesn't work very well with our tooling.

The easiest way for our tooling is to have the split out repos available somewhere it can be cloned from. Most projects just put it up on github temporarily, but you can use anywhere.

Cheers,
Josh"}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2015-04-20 06:36:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2015-04-20 06:42:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The new project was splited and placed in github temporarily.

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-20 06:49:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Some help is here: https://help.github.com/articles/splitting-a-subfolder-out-into-a-new-repository/"}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2015-04-27 04:58:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi Joshua,

The git filter-branch worked correctly.

If you look into the old project - https://github.com/stackforge/zvm-driver, you will find there's no useful history info in it either, just one commit submitted a snapshot of the code.

And we are not quite care about the history info(I've explained this in my early comments). Our goal is to create the new projects, then we can start to development on stackforge from L release.

Thanks.
Rui"}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2015-04-28 04:24:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

My apologies, I assumed there would be more commits. The history is actually important, even if seemingly not useful to the project. It provides a history of who authored what.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-04-28 07:06:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

This looks fine in general but I noticed one issue with naming:

We have a convention to name all neutron plugins as networking-NAME, so instead of neutron-zvm-plugin, it should be networking-zvm. Have a look at the existing repositories already...

Could you rename, please?'}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2015-04-28 07:12:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

commit_message:
Create networking-zvm project on StackForge

This project implements zVM ML2 mechanism driver and zVM neutron
agent for OpenStack Neutron.

This project is separated from existing stackforge/zvm-driver. Will
submit another change to move stackforge/zvm-driver to attic after
this project created.

Change-Id: I9ec6f40b9821f2aad5ee814aff3d8374362f1287

I just checked oslo.db. The juno branch has no py34 env in tox.ini and test-requirements.txt uses MySQL-python which doesn't work on Python 3. The kilo branch has a py34 env in tox.ini. and uses PyMySQL which works on Python 3.

Is it a problem that oslo.db has no py34 env in tox.ini but has a python3 voting job for the juno branch?

commit_message:
Add `LogCatcher' context manager

Add `LogCatcher' context manager that records all the log messages
issued by the code inside the context. User can then check if there
is a message with the particular content or simply retrieve all
 messages.

Change-Id: If0bb5f3e8f4d8a61aa3639340b2c8a4250cb3153
Closes-Bug: #1449009

commit_message:
Let kolla-release create branches

Kolla branches cannot currently be created because the ACLs are not
appropritae for doing so.  We are branching Kolla asap so need to
be able to create the stable/kilo branch.

Change-Id: Ib0269f289b07fd1420086111b1e2cfe144731a6b

commit_message:
Use zaqar's devstack plugin

Zaqar's team is in the process of moving devstack's zaqar code into a
plugin. This patch changes the gate job to make it consume such plugin.
The plugin already landed in Zaqar's code base as per
I38c6cf71e2ae73f60e4494d853fee5796aa1f0f8

Change-Id: If5c91ebe136017cea2eeecf62a580d050e49617d

commit_message:
Add keystoneauth library and testing infrastructure

Add the keystoneauth library and testing. This is meant to split out the
auth-specifics from keystoneclient and made as lightweight as possible.
This is the initial split, cleanup and trimming down will be handled in
gerrit.

Change-Id: I9bce17c37c7d5cbda3a5e32ebbab8a4fa5daac44

commit_message:
ceilometer: Use http session in dispatcher

The ceilometer dipatcher needs to do between 2 to 5 http requests
for each samples. Current it use the basic API of the python-requests
library, that creates 1 tcp connections for each http requests.
Connections are pooled by default (10 simultaneous connections) and
a error is raised when the pool is exhausted.

This change move to the session API of python-requests to
creates only one tcp connection per ceilometer-collector workers,
and block when the pool exhausts.

Change-Id: I8255622cf57082785b48754d9e506413ee9122a7

commit_message:
Add FIP/SNAT using legacy network controller.

This patch uses the L3NatAgent in no-dvr mode to implement the FIP/NAT.
The L3ControllerAgent class extends the L3NatAgent and only synchronize the data to the SDN controller.

Closes-Bug: #1438065
Closes-Bug: #1438523

commit_message:
Add nginx container to supervisord config

Fixes regression in Ia839cc2aa4e584b7b01793a5738f6542b9a07c8e
which consolidated supervisor configuration for docker
containers.

commit_message:
Streamline and simplify package filtering api

Introduce catalogue parameter to allow distinguishing between catalogue
of applications (packages that one can deploy) and managable-apps
(packages that one can edit).
Streamline include_disabled filtering.
Allow filtering out your own packages for admin requests.

Change-Id: Ica031058d963246ff4d76e52cfc8b8b44d207c9a
Partial-Bug: #1448226
Relates-Bug: #1448135

Show 'reserved' status in os-fixed-ips API

Show the 'reserved' status on a FixedIP object in the os-fixed-ips API
extension. The extension allows one to reserve and unreserve a fixed IP
but the show method does not report the current status.

APIImpact

Spec for blueprint show-reserved-status-in-os-fixed-ips-api

Change-Id: Idb0d74414ecbc732b9548bcb103072be80432af9

Remove usage of dict for gnocchi object

Ensure we always use the sqlalchemy object and not
the dict interface provided by oslo.db model.

commit_message:
Ceph: use the admin port for communication with Keystone

Current port, 5000, is meant to be used for public requests. 35357
should be used instead.

Reference: http://ceph.com/docs/master/radosgw/keystone/

Change-Id: I1ef8030b39256a17ef3b1dc1e1061c756d7392a6
Closes-Bug: 1446704

commit_message:
Load archive_policy named resource metric

If the orm object of a metric is loaded with a resource,
the joinedload of the resource doesn't include the archive_policy.

This change load the archive_policy when we ask for a metric attached
to a resource.

Closes-bug: #1449452
Change-Id: Ic48f43048fe3e14b42b347cf44250183de60f9d8

commit_message:
Fixed errors in packages/deb and mirror/ubuntu

1) unconditional rebuilding due to
never existent file

repocleanup.done used to depend on PHONY target (sources)
which led to unconditional rebuilding.
This didn't influence ISO builds because CI always cleans
environment.

2) fail when try to rebuild second
time without cleaning environment

repo.done used to consume some config files
created by reprepro.done target. After consuming those files
it used to remove them not touching reprepro.done itself.
Without cleaning build environment this fails the build process.

Change-Id: Ib0de2e5ea94caeb7f93f5bc8d0f06a6f806e3ca6
Closes-Bug: #1448206

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

commit_message:
Don't query compute_node through service object in nova-manage

The relationship between compute_node and service tables was
removed in a recent commit and to be able to remove compat code in
the objects, calls to get them should be done directly instead of
going through one or the other.

Since we are really just interested in the compute_node object here
this in addition saves us one extra db call.

Change-Id: I5270882321f7d16f993746498f751f17b0cb52fd
Related-Bug: #1438189

One comment inline + could you please add this metric to the tables in the HTML reports? See this module: https://github.com/stackforge/rally/blob/master/rally/benchmark/processing/plot.py'}, {'account_id': 8840, 'date': '2015-03-07 22:12:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

Sure, I can add median to the HTML report, shouldn't be that hard.

I put median in that order, after Boris agreed to it.

Now, I also feel is not necessarily in order, since median really is a 50% percentile. Also, mean, or the average, is kind of the only metric that doesn't 'fit' in this order, since it is a measure of central tendency, and not about order statistics ,like min,median,percentiles,max.

That being said, here's how I would sort them.

Mean, Count, Errors | Min, Median, 90%ile, 95%ile, Max

or

Min, Median, 90%ile, 95%ile, Max | Mean, Count, Errors - (personally I prefer this one)

Arranging them in these orders implies that (mean, count, errors) is different from the others, since (mean, count, errors) doesn't really tell you anything about order, while the others do. (For more info, Google 'order statistics', and/or 'non-parametric statistics'. Very important for data that is not normally distributed, like latency). If we later add other metrics such as confidence intervals, or other nonparametric metrics, I think they would fit  in the (mean, count, errors) group.

I'm open to suggestions :)"}, {'account_id': 8507, 'date': '2015-03-08 09:25:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Carlos, yep, what you're saying makes sense from the statistical point of view, and I like the idea of grouping the order statistics together. I'd personally prefer the second design you suggested, but let's see what other cores think about this."}, {'account_id': 8840, 'date': '2015-03-11 17:14:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 8840, 'date': '2015-03-11 17:15:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 14817, 'date': '2015-03-11 17:37:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1
